\rem /s1 Aaron Offers Sacrifices; Aaron's Priesthood Inaugurated; The Priests Begin Their Work; The Priests Begin Their Ministry
\p
\v 1 On the eighth¦49981 day¦49980, Mosheh¦49983 summoned¦49982 Aharon and his sons¦49985, along with Yisrael's elders¦49986,
\v 2 and he told Aharon, “Get a healthy, \add ≈young¦49997\add*, male calf for a sin offering for yourself¦49995, and a ram \add ≈without¦50003 defects¦50003\add* for a burnt¦50002 offering, and present¦50004 them to Yahweh¦50006.
\v 3 Then¦50008 tell the \add ≈Israeli¦50010 people¦50010\add* to take a male goat¦50015 for a sin offering, and a calf and a lamb¦50020, both a year old and \add ≈without¦50024 defects¦50024\add* for a burnt¦50025 offering,
\v 4 as well as a bull¦50027 and a ram to sacrifice¦50030 to Yahweh as peace¦50029 offerings¦50029, and a grain¦50033 offering¦50033 mixed¦50034 will oil¦50035, because¦50036 Yahweh will appear¦50039 to you all today.”
\p
\v 5 \add ≈So¦50042\add* they brought \add everything\add* to the \add ≈sacred¦50050\add* tent¦50050 that¦50044 Mosheh¦50046 had \add ≈instructed¦50045\add* them, and¦50042 the whole assembly presented them as they stood¦50056 \add ≈before\add* Yahweh¦50058,
\v 6 then¦50060 Mosheh¦50061 said¦50060, “You've¦50072 done what Yahweh¦50067 told¦50066 you, so now you'll all see his \add ≈brightness\add* appear¦50069.”
\v 7 Then \add *he\add* told¦50102 Aharon, “\add ≈Go\add* to the altar¦50082 and make your sin offering and your burnt¦50089 offering to make \add ≈yourself¦50091 and the people right with God\add*. Then make the people's offering to make \add ≈them right with God\add*, just as Yahweh¦50103 commanded¦50102.”\x + \xo 9:7: \xt Heb 7:27.\x*
\p
\v 8 \add ≈So¦50105\add* Aharon¦50106 approached the altar¦50109 and¦50110 slaughtered the calf for his own sin¦50114 offering¦50114,
\v 9 and¦50119 \add *his\add* sons presented¦50119 the blood to him. Dipping¦50121 his finger¦50127 into the blood, he \add ≈smeared\add* it on the altar's \add four\add* \add ≈projecting corners\add*, then¦50119 he poured¦50137 \add the rest of\add* the blood out at the altar's base.
\v 10 He burnt up the fat and the kidneys¦50148, and the lobe from the liver¦50154 for the sin¦50157 offering¦50157 on the altar¦50159, just as Yahweh¦50162 had instructed¦50161 Mosheh¦50165,
\v 11 \add ≈but¦50167\add* the meat¦50169 and¦50167 the skin¦50172, he burnt¦50173 up in a fire¦50174 outside¦50175 the camp¦50176.
\p
\v 12 Then¦50184 \add ?@Aharon\add* slaughtered the burnt¦50181 offering¦50181, and \add *his\add* sons¦50183 brought¦50182 the blood¦50188 to him and he splashed it on \add ≈each side of\add* the altar¦50192.
\v 13 Then¦50195 they brought¦50198 him the head¦50203 and the \add cut-up\add* pieces¦50200, and he burnt¦50197 them up on the altar¦50207.
\v 14 He washed¦50209 the innards and the legs, and then¦50209 \add also\add* burnt¦50219 them up on the altar¦50220.
\p
\v 15 Then¦50222 \add @Aharon\add* presented¦50222 the people's offering. He took the goat¦50229 for the people's offering and¦50222 slaughtered it, then¦50222 offered it as a sin offering like \add ≈the other one\add*.
\v 16 He presented¦50237 the burnt¦50240 offering¦50240—following all the \add ≈instructions\add* when he did it.
\v 17 Then¦50244 he presented¦50244 the grain¦50247 offering, and¦50244 \add ≈taking a large handful\add*, he burnt it on the altar¦50254, in addition¦50244 to the morning's¦50257 burnt offering.
\v 18 Then¦50259 \add Aharon¦50272\add* slaughtered the bull¦50262 and the ram \add which¦50268\add* were the people's¦50269 peace¦50267 offering¦50267, and \add *his\add* sons¦50271 brought¦50270 the blood¦50275 to him and he splashed it on \add ≈each side of\add* the altar¦50280.\x + \xo 9:18: \xt Lev 3:1-11.\x*
\v 19 He took the fat from the bull¦50288 and the ram, including¦50289 their fatty tails and \add @the fat\add* covering¦50293 the innards, the kidneys¦50294, and the lobe of the liver¦50296,
\v 20 and¦50305 placed¦50298 it \add all\add* on top of \add &those animals\add* breast¦50304 \add meat\add*, then¦50298 burnt up \add @the fat\add* on the altar¦50307.
\v 21 \add ≈Finally¦50315,\add* he raised the breast¦50310 \add meat\add* and¦50309 the right¦50313 thigh¦50312 as a wave offering \add in front¦50317\add* of Yahweh¦50318, just as Mosheh¦50321 had \add ≈instructed¦50320\add*.
\p
\v 22 Then¦50323 Aharon¦50324 raised his \add ≈arms\add* towards the people¦50331 and blessed¦50332 them, and then¦50323 he \add ≈stepped\add* down, \add having finished\add* making the sin offering, the burnt¦50336 offering, and the peace¦50337 offerings¦50337.\x + \xo 9:22: \xt Num 6:22-26.\x*
\v 23 Mosheh¦50340 and Aharon¦50341 entered the \add ≈sacred¦50344\add* tent, and \add when\add* they came \add back\add* out, they blessed¦50347 the people and Yahweh's¦50354 \add ≈brilliance\add* appeared¦50351 to all the people.
\v 24 Then¦50361 flames¦50362 \add ≈shot out\add* from Yahweh's¦50364 front and \add ≈evaporated\add* the burnt¦50371 offering¦50371 and the fat on the altar¦50368. They people¦50378 saw¦50375 that \add happen\add*, and they yelled out and fell down \add onto their knees\add* \add ≈with their faces¦50383 to the ground\add*.
\c 10
\s1 Nadav and Avihu get destroyed
\rem /s1 The Death of Nadab and Abihu; Nadab and Abihu; The Sin of Nadab and Abihu
\p
\v 1 Then¦50385 two of Aharon's sons, Nadav and Avihu each took their \add ≈incense-burning pans\add* and put fire in them, and put incense on \add @the fire\add*, \add ≈thus offering unauthorised\add* fire to Yahweh¦50401 that¦50404 he hadn't instructed¦50406 them to do.
\v 2 \add ≈So¦50409\add* flames¦50410 \add ≈shot out\add* from Yahweh's¦50412 front and¦50409 consumed then¦50409 \add ≈so\add* they¦50415 died¦50415 \add there\add* \add ≈in front\add* of Yahweh.
\v 3 Then¦50419 Mosheh¦50420 told Aharon, “That's what Yahweh¦50428 \add ≈meant when he said¦50419\add*, ‘I will \add ≈reveal\add* my holiness to those¦50431 who approach me, then¦50419 I'll¦50432 be honoured \add ≈in the sight of\add* all the people¦50438.’ ”
\p
\v 4 Then¦50443 Mosheh¦50444 \add ≈summoned\add* Mishael¦50447 and Elitsafan, the sons of Aharon's Uncle Uzziyel, and told them, “\add ≈Come and help by carrying¦50457\add* your cousins' \add bodies\add* from the sacred¦50464 place \add here\add* to a place outside¦50467 the camp¦50468.”
\v 5 \add ≈So¦50470\add* they \add ≈came\add* and¦50470 carried¦50471 the two corpses by their¦50472 clothes to a place outside¦50475 the camp¦50476 just as Mosheh¦50479 had told them to do.
\p
\v 6 Then¦50481 Mosheh¦50482 told Aharon and his sons¦50489 Eleazar¦50486 and Itamar¦50487, “Don't¦50491 \add ≈leave your hair\add* loose, and don't¦50491 tear your clothes¦50495, so that you won't die¦50500 and \add ≡so that\add* \add @Yahweh\add* won't be angry at the entire¦50502 community. But¦50481 \add ≈meanwhile\add*, all the \add ≈Israelis¦50509\add* must¦50500 \add ≈mourn¦50511\add* because Yahweh \add ≈was angry enough to burn\add* \add those two\add*.
\v 7 \add ≈Also¦50519,\add* don't¦50522 leave the entrance¦50519 to the \add ≈sacred¦50520\add* tent¦50520, as you might die¦50526 because¦50527 you all \add still\add* have Yahweh's¦50531 anointing¦50530 oil¦50529 on you.” \add ≈So¦50519\add* they¦50533 did¦50533 \add ≈everything that Mosheh¦50535 said\add*.
\s1 Instructions for priests
\rem /s1 Instructions for Priestly Conduct; Rules for Priests
\p
\v 8 Then Yahweh¦50539 told Aharon,
\v 9 “\add Neither\add* you or your sons¦50553 should drink wine or strong¦50546 drink when you're \add going to\add* go into the \add ≈sacred¦50558\add* tent¦50558 so that you won't¦50547 die¦50561. This regulation¦50562 is permanent¦50563 \add ≈and for future\add* generations¦50564.
\v 10 You must \add carefully\add* \add ≈distinguish\add* between what's sacred¦50568 and what's common, and what's ‘unclean¦50572’ and ‘clean¦50574’.
\v 11 and¦50576 you must teach¦50576 the \add ≈Israelis¦50579\add* all the instructions¦50584 that¦50585 Yahweh¦50587 has \add ≈given\add* them \add ≈via\add* Mosheh¦50591.”
\p
\v 12 Then Mosheh¦50595 told Aharon and his \add ≈remaining¦50606\add* sons¦50605 Eleazar¦50600 and Itamar¦50603, “Take the remainder of the grain¦50610 offering¦50610 after \add the memorial portion has been given\add* to Yahweh¦50613, and eat¦50614 that¦50611 \add ≈flat bread¦50615\add* \add there\add* beside¦50616 the altar¦50617, because¦50618 it's \add ≈very sacred¦50619\add*.\x + \xo 10:12-13: \xt Lev 6:14-18.\x*
\v 13 You all must¦50623 eat¦50623 it in a sacred¦50626 place¦50625, because it's the portion for you and¦50623 your sons¦50631 from the gifts to Yahweh¦50634, because that's what I've¦50638 been instructed¦50638.
\v 14 \add ≈Also¦50640\add*, you all must¦50647 eat the breast¦50641 \add meat\add* from the wave offering and the thigh¦50645 from the contribution¦50646 \add offering\add* in a ‘clean’ place¦50648. Your¦50664 sons and daughters¦50652 \add ≈can join you all for that\add*, because¦50654 \add @that food\add* has been given¦50660 as the portion for you and your children¦50659 from the peace¦50662 offering sacrifices¦50661 from the \add ≈Israelis¦50663\add*.\x + \xo 10:14-15: \xt Lev 7:30-34.\x*
\v 15 \add Yes,\add* \add &those\add* \add #thighs\add* from the contribution¦50667 \add offering\add* and the breast¦50668 \add meat\add* from the wave offering, in addition to the gifts of the fat portions, must¦50673 be brought before Yahweh as a raised offering, and then they'll always¦50684 become the portion for you and your families, just as Yahweh instructed¦50686.”
\p
\v 16 Then¦50689 Mosheh¦50695 looked for the goat¦50691 \add meat\add* from the sin¦50692 offering¦50692, \add ≈but¦50689 was shocked to discover\add* that it had been burnt¦50697 up \add on the altar\add*, \add ≈so\add* he was angry¦50698 with Aharon's¦50706 remaining¦50707 sons¦50705 Eleazar¦50701 and¦50689 Itamar¦50704, telling them,
\v 17 “Why didn't¦50711 you eat¦50713 \add &that\add* sin¦50716 offering¦50716 in the sacred place¦50717, because¦50719 it's \add ≈very\add* sacred and he gave¦50725 it to you to bear the community's \add ≈guilt\add* then to \add ≈make them right with\add* Yahweh¦50735.\x + \xo 10:17: \xt Lev 6:24-26.\x*
\v 18 Listen here! Its blood¦50743 \em wasn't\em* taken into the inner sacred place, \add so\add* you must¦50749 eat it in the sacred place just like I told¦50753 you to do!”
\p
\v 19 Then¦50755 Aharon \add ≈explained\add* to Mosheh¦50759, “Listen, they presented¦50762 their sin offering and their burnt¦50768 offering to Yahweh today, and \add ≈yet I lost two of my sons\add*. But¦50755 if I'd eaten the sin offering today, would it have \add ≈pleased\add* Yahweh?”
\v 20 \add ≈When¦50781\add* Mosheh¦50782 heard \add <that\add*, \add ≈he was satisfied\add*.
\c 11
\s1 Creatures that may be eaten
\rem /s1 Animals That May Be Eaten; Ceremonially Clean and Unclean Animals; Clean and Unclean Foods; Clean and Unclean Food; Purification and atonement
\r (Deu. 14:3-21)
\p
\v 1 Then Yahweh¦50788 told Mosheh¦50791 and Aharon:
\p
\v 2 Tell¦50802 the \add ≈Israelis¦50801\add* that \add ≈the following\add* creatures¦50805 on the earth¦50814 are the ones that you all can eat¦50807:
\v 3 ⇔You all can eat¦50827 any animal¦50825 that has hooves¦50822 \add ≈which are completely split in two¦50818\add* and¦50820 that \add also\add* \add ≈chew\add* the cud.
\v 4 However you mustn't eat¦50834 those \add ≈without \+em both¦50837\+em* traits\add*, for example camels¦50841 \add ≈chew\add* the cud \add ≈but¦50837\add* don't¦50833 have divided¦50837 hooves¦50838, \add so\add* they are ‘unclean¦50850’ for you.
\v 5 The rock¦50856 badger¦50856 \add ≈likewise\add*, because¦50857 although it \add ≈chews\add* the cud, it \add too\add* doesn't have divided¦50864 hooves¦50862,
\v 6 and¦50869 the rabbit is ‘unclean¦50880’ for you all because¦50872 although it \add ≈chews\add* the cud, it doesn't have divided¦50879 hooves¦50877.
\v 7 \add #Pigs\add* have divided¦50889 \add #hooves\add* that are split completely, \add ≈but¦50884\add* don't¦50897 \add ≈chew\add* the cud, \add so\add* they're ‘unclean¦50900’ for you all—
\v 8 you mustn't eat their meat or touch¦50909 their carcasses¦50907 \add because\add* they're ‘unclean¦50910’ for you all.
\p
\v 9 ⇔You all can eat everything that \add lives\add* in the water, \add whether\add* the oceans or rivers, as long as it has \add both\add* fins and scales¦50926.
\v 10 \add ≈In contrast,\add* anything in the oceans or rivers without \add both\add* fins and¦50933 scales¦50939, whether they're swarming¦50943 creatures¦50946 or otherwise, they'll \add all\add* be detestable¦50950 for you all.
\v 11 \add ≈So¦50954\add* anything that's detestable to you all, you mustn't eat their meat and¦50954 you must¦50955 detest¦50954 their carcasses¦50962.
\v 12 Anything in the water¦50972 that doesn't have \add both\add* fins and¦50971 scales¦50971 will be detestable¦50973 for you all.
\p
\v 13 From the birds, the ones that you'll all detest¦50980 and avoid eating will include: the eagle¦50990 and \add ≈any kind of\add* vulture,
\v 14 the kite and¦51000 any kind of falcon,
\v 15 any kind of crow,
\v 16 \add ≈any kind of\add* owl, gull, or hawk,
\v 17 the cormorant¦51030,
\v 18 the osprey,
\v 19 the stork¦51046, any kind of heron¦51047, the hoopoe¦51051, and¦51045 bats.
\v 20 Everything¦51056 that¦51059 swarms¦51057 with wings and walks¦51059 on four¦51062 \add legs\add* must be detestable¦51063 for you all.
\v 21 However, you all can eat¦51072 anything that swarms¦51074 with wings and walks¦51076 on four¦51079 \add legs\add* that has its legs above¦51085 its feet¦51086 for hopping on the ground.
\v 22 You all can eat any kind of locust or cricket or grasshopper¦51112,
\v 23 \add ≈but¦51115\add* anything that¦51118 swarms¦51116 with wings and¦51115 walks on four¦51121 \add legs\add* must be detestable¦51123 for you all.
\rem /s1 Unclean Animals
\p
\v 24 \add ≈The following\add* will make you¦51128 ‘unclean’—anyone¦51131 who touches¦51131 their¦51132 carcasses¦51132 will become ‘unclean’ until¦51134 the evening¦51136,
\v 25 plus¦51144 anyone¦51140 who carries¦51140 their carcass¦51141 must¦51142 wash their clothes¦51143 and¦51138 will be ‘unclean¦51144’ until¦51145 the evening¦51147:
\v 26 Any animal with a divided¦51154 hoof¦51155 but¦51156 not \add ≈completely split in two¦51154\add* or that¦51152 doesn't \add ≈chew\add* the cud will be ‘unclean’ for you all—anyone¦51168 who touches¦51168 them will become ‘unclean’.
\v 27 \add ≈Also¦51172,\add* any four-footed animal that¦51174 walks on its paws is ‘unclean’ for you—anyone¦51174 who touches¦51190 their¦51191 carcass¦51191 will become ‘unclean’ until¦51193 the evening¦51195,
\v 28 plus¦51203 anyone¦51197 who carries¦51197 their carcass¦51200 must¦51201 wash their clothes¦51202 and¦51197 will be ‘unclean’ until¦51204 the evening¦51206 \add because\add* they're ‘unclean’ for you all.
\p
\v 29 These are the ‘unclean¦51214’ creatures from the ones that¦51216 swarm¦51216 on the ground: \add #rats, mice, lizards¦51222\add*
\v 30 of any kind, \add #geckos, skinks¦51228, and¦51225 chameleons¦51229\add*.
\v 31 Out of all the swarming¦51236 things¦51236, those are ‘unclean’ for you—anyone¦51239 who touches¦51239 them when they've died will be ‘unclean’ until¦51243 the evening¦51245.
\v 32 \add ≈Also¦51247,\add* anything that¦51272 \add ≈their¦51255 dead bodies\add* fall on will become ‘unclean’, whether it's a wooden. cloth, leader, or sackcloth¦51268 object, or any container used for work¦51275, \add so then¦51247\add* it must¦51250 be immersed in water¦51277 and¦51247 it will be ‘unclean’ until¦51280 the evening¦51282 when it will become ‘clean’ \add again\add*.
\v 33 \add If\add* one of \add @those creatures\add* falls into a clay container, everything in it will become ‘unclean¦51300’ and¦51285 you must¦51292 break¦51302 \add @that container\add*.
\v 34 If water¦51312 from \add that container\add* got onto any food, it will become ‘unclean’, and any drink¦51316 \add ≈take\add* from that container will be ‘unclean’.
\v 35 Anything that the dead body of one of \add @those creatures\add* falls onto will become ‘unclean’—any oven or stove¦51333 must¦51327 be smashed. They have become ‘unclean’ \add ≈and¦51324 would always remain so\add*.
\v 36 However a spring¦51342 or a cistern¦51343 for collecting¦51344 water¦51346 will be ‘clean’, \add ≈but¦51343\add* anyone¦51349 touching¦51349 that dead body will be ‘unclean¦51351’.
\v 37 If the dead body fell on some seeds that will be planted, \add @that seed\add* is still ‘clean’,
\v 38 \add ≈but¦51367\add* if the seeds \add ≈are wet\add* when the dead body falls on it, then¦51367 it's ‘unclean¦51377’ for you.
\p
\v 39 If any animal that¦51387 you all can eat dies, then any person touches¦51392 its¦51393 carcass¦51393 will be ‘unclean¦51394’ until¦51395 the evening¦51397.
\v 40 Anyone¦51399 who eats¦51399 any \add part\add* of that dead body, and anyone¦51399 who \add ≈moves\add* it, must¦51401 wash their clothes¦51402 and will be ‘unclean’ until the evening.
\p
\v 41 Every creature that¦51421 swarms¦51420 along the ground is detestable¦51425—it mustn't be eaten¦51428.
\v 42 Everything that \add moves\add* on its belly, and any swarming thing that moves along the ground on four¦51441 or more feet mustn't be eaten because they're detestable.
\v 43 Don't¦51461 make yourselves detestable¦51463 with any of those swarming¦51469 creatures, and don't¦51461 make yourselves ‘unclean’ by \add touching or eating\add* them,
\v 44 because I am your god¦51480 Yahweh¦51479. You all must¦51481 keep¦51481 yourselves holy, and you're a holy people because I'm holy. \add ≈So\add* don't¦51487 make yourselves ‘unclean¦51488’ with any swarming¦51494 creatures that creep¦51495 across the ground\x + \xo 11:44: \xt Lev 19:2; 1Pe 1:16.\x*
\v 45 because I am Yahweh¦51503, the one who brought¦51504 you all out of Egypt¦51507 to be your god¦51510, and you must¦51511 be holy because I am holy.
\p
\v 46 The \add above\add* are the regulations about livestock, birds, creatures that move in the water¦51525, and creatures that swarm¦51529 across the ground,
\v 47 to \add ≈distinguish\add* between the ‘unclean¦51536’ and the ‘clean’, i.e., those that can be eaten and those that must¦51546 not be eaten.
\c 12
\s1 Purification after giving birth
\rem /s1 The Purification of Women after Childbirth; Purification after Childbirth; Purification of Women after Childbirth; Purification After Childbirth
\p
\v 1 Then Yahweh¦51550 told Mosheh¦51553:
\p
\v 2 Tell¦51560 the \add ≈Israelis¦51559\add* that when a woman¦51562 gets pregnant and then gives birth to a boy, she will then be ‘unclean’ for seven¦51568 days similar to how her impurity¦51571 during her \add ≈monthly period\add* makes her ‘unclean’.
\v 3 Then¦51575 on the eighth¦51576 day¦51575, \add @the baby boy's\add* foreskin¦51579 must¦51577 be circumcised¦51577.\x + \xo 12:3: \xt Gen 17:12; Luk 2:21.\x*
\v 4 \add @The mother\add* will remain¦51585 impure from the blood¦51586 for thirty-three days—she must¦51585 not touch¦51593 any sacred¦51590 thing¦51590 and¦51581 may not enter the sanctuary¦51596 until¦51599 her¦51602 purification time¦51584 is completed¦51601.
\p
\v 5 \add ≈However,\add* if she gave birth to a \add ≈girl\add*, she'll be ‘unclean¦51609’ for two¦51610 weeks¦51610 similar to how her impurity¦51611 during her \add ≈monthly period\add*, and¦51605 her purification¦51620 time¦51615 will be sixty-six days¦51615.
\p
\v 6 When¦51622 \add @the mother's\add* purification¦51625 time¦51624 is completed¦51622 for either a son or a daughter¦51628, she must¦51629 take a one-year-old lamb as a burnt¦51634 offering and¦51622 a \add ≈young¦51635\add* pigeon or dove as a sin offering to the priest¦51650 at the entrance¦51644 to the \add ≈sacred¦51645\add* tent.
\v 7 Then¦51652 he must¦51652 present¦51652 them to Yahweh¦51654 to \add ≈make her right with God\add*, and¦51652 then¦51652 she'll be purified from her flow of blood¦51659. That's the regulation for a woman who gives¦51662 birth¦51662 to either a male or a female¦51665.
\p
\v 8 If \add ≈she's unable to afford\add* a lamb, then she must¦51670 take \em two\em* young¦51680 pigeons or doves—one for the burnt¦51683 offering and one for the sin offering. Then¦51667 the priest¦51688 will \add ≈make her¦51671 right with God\add*, and then she'll will have been purified.\x + \xo 12:8: \xt Luk 2:24.\x*
\c 13
\s1 Regulations about skin diseases
\rem /s1 Laws concerning Skin Diseases; Contagious Skin Diseases; Leprosy, Varieties and Symptoms; Regulations About Infectious Skin Diseases
\p
\v 1 Then Yahweh¦51693 told Mosheh¦51696 and Aharon:
\p
\v 2 If \add someone discovers\add* a raised area on their skin, or a scab or a bright¦51714 spot, and it seems like an infectious skin disease¦51720, then \add @that person\add* should be taken to a priest¦51725 (Aharon or one of his sons¦51730),
\v 3 and the priest must \add ≈examine\add* their skin. If the hair¦51741 in the infected \add spot\add* has turned¦51743 white¦51745 and the infection appears¦51746 to be deeper under the skin, then¦51733 it's \add confirmed as\add* an infectious skin disease¦51752 and \add ≈so\add* the priest must pronounce the person as ‘unclean¦51756’.
\v 4 \add However,\add* if it's a white spot \add ≈that doesn't seem\add* to be deep, and¦51759 the hair¦51773 hasn't turned¦51776 white, then¦51759 the priest¦51779 \add must¦51778 order\add* the person to be quarantined for seven¦51783 days¦51784.
\v 5 Then¦51786 on the seventh day¦51788, if the infection is still there but¦51786 hasn't spread¦51796, then¦51786 the priest¦51787 \add must¦51786 order\add* a further seven¦51801 days¦51802 of quarantine.
\v 6 After that next seven¦51809 days, if the infection has faded and not spread¦51816, the priest¦51806 must pronounce the person as ‘clean’—it was just a \add ≈sore\add* so the person must wash their clothes¦51824 and then¦51805 they'll be ‘clean’.
\v 7 \add ≈However,\add* if the spot does spread across the skin \em after¦51833\em* the priest has pronounced \add @the person\add* to be ‘clean’, then¦51827 they must¦51830 \add ≈return\add* to the priest a second¦51840 time.
\v 8 The priest must re-examine \add @that person\add* and¦51845 if the spot on the skin has spread¦51848, then¦51845 the priest must pronounce them ‘unclean¦51851’ because they have a skin disease¦51853.
\p
\v 9 Anyone who develops an infectious skin disease¦51858 must¦51860 be taken to a priest¦51865
\v 10 \add ≈to be examined\add*. If it's a white spot on the skin and the hair¦51876 has turned¦51875 white, and there's raw flesh¦51879 \add visible\add* in the swelling,
\v 11 then it's a chronic skin disease¦51883, and the priest¦51889 must¦51888 pronounce \add @that person\add* as ‘unclean’ and can't¦51890 just be \add temporarily\add* \add ≈quarantined\add*.
\v 12 \add ≈However,\add* if the disease has broken out and¦51896 spread across the entire¦51905 \add ≈body\add* from head¦51909 to toe as far as can be observed by the priest¦51917,
\v 13 then¦51919 \add after\add* the priest's¦51920 confirmation that it covers¦51922 the entire¦51926 \add ≈body¦51928\add*, \add @that person\add* can be pronounced as ‘clean’ \add again\add* as all of it has turned¦51934 white¦51935.
\v 14 \add ≈However,\add* if any raw flesh¦51942 \add ≈shows itself\add*, then¦51939 they'll become ‘unclean¦51944’ \add ≈that same\add* day¦51939.
\v 15 The priest¦51947 must \add ≈examine\add* that raw flesh and¦51952 must pronounce \add @that person\add* as ‘unclean’ due to \add &their\add* skin disease¦51957.
\v 16 \add ≈Afterwards, if it heals over\add* and goes white¦51966, then they can return¦51962 to the priest¦51970
\v 17 \add ≈to be reexamined\add*, and if the infection has indeed gone white¦51977, then¦51972 the priest¦51973 can pronounce it as \add ≈not being infectious\add* and \add @the person\add* as ‘clean’ \add again\add*.
\p
\v 18 When \add ≈someone\add* has a boil on their skin, \add ≈but¦51987\add* it heals
\v 19 \add ≈leaving behind\add* a white swelling¦52000 or a reddish-white bright¦52003 spot, then¦51997 \add @that person\add* must¦52006 show themself to the priest¦52009.
\v 20 The priest will \add ≈examine\add* it, and if it is indeed more than \add just\add* skin deep and its hair¦52019 has turned¦52020 white¦52021, then¦52011 the priest must¦52011 pronounce \add @that person\add* as ‘unclean¦52022’ because an infectious skin disease¦52026 has broken¦52029 out from the \add original\add* boil.
\v 21 \add ≈However,\add* if the priest's examination finds not white¦52040 hair¦52039 on it, and it's not more than skin deep, and it's fading, then¦52031 he will \add order\add* \add @that person\add* quarantined for seven¦52050 days¦52051,
\v 22 and¦52053 if it spreads further on \add &their\add* skin, then¦52053 the priest¦52059 must¦52056 declare¦52058 \add @that person\add* as ‘unclean¦52058’ because it's \add ≈infectious\add*.
\v 23 \add ≈But¦52064\add* if the bright¦52068 spot \add ≈hasn't spread¦52070\add* \add during the quarantine\add*, then¦52064 it's \add just\add* the scar from the boil and¦52074 the priest¦52075 can pronounce \add @the person\add* as ‘clean’.
\p
\v 24 If someone gets a burn on their skin, and the burn area becomes reddish-white or a white spot,
\v 25 then the priest must examine it, and if the hair¦52101 on the spot has turned¦52100 white¦52102 and \add @the infection\add* looks more than skin deep, then a skin disease has broken¦52112 out in the burn¦52111, and the priest must pronounce \add @that person\add* as ‘unclean¦52113’ because it's \add ≈infectious\add*.
\v 26 \add ≈However,\add* if the priest¦52123 sees that there's¦52125 no white¦52129 hair¦52128 in the spot, and it's not more than skin deep, and it's fading, then¦52120 \add *he\add* will \add order\add* \add @that person\add* quarantined for seven¦52139 days¦52140.
\v 27 On the seventh¦52145 day¦52144, the priest¦52143 will re-examine \add @the person\add*, and¦52151 if it's spread further, \add *he\add* must¦52142 pronounce \add @that person\add* as ‘unclean¦52151’ because it's an infectious skin disease¦52155.
\v 28 \add ≈But¦52158\add* if the bright¦52162 spot hasn't spread¦52165 on the skin, and¦52158 it faded \add more\add*, then¦52158 it was \add just\add* swelling¦52169 from the burn. Then¦52158 the priest¦52173 will pronounce \add @that person\add* to be ‘clean’ because¦52174 it was \add just\add* the scar \add ≈caused by\add* \add &their\add* burn.
\p
\v 29 If a man or woman¦52183 has an infection in \add &their\add* \add ≈scalp\add* or \add ≈under\add* \add &their\add* beard¦52191,
\v 30 then the priest should inspect the infection. If it appears¦52199 to be more than skin deep, and there's any thin yellow¦52206 hairs in it, then the priest must¦52193 pronounce \add @that person\add* as ‘unclean¦52208’ \add because\add* it's a \add ≈itchy and infectious\add* skin infection on the \add ≈scalp or face\add*.
\v 31 \add ≈However,\add* if the priest¦52222 notices an itchy infection yet it's only skin deep and¦52219 there's¦52237 no black¦52236 hair¦52235 on it, then¦52219 he should quarantine that person for seven¦52245 days¦52246.
\v 32 On the seventh¦52254 day¦52253, the priest¦52249 will re-examine \add ≈that person\add* and if the spot hasn't widened and \add still\add* only appears¦52266 to be skin deep,
\v 33 then \add @that person\add* should shave \add their head\add*, and¦52274 then the priest¦52281 should quarantine them for a further seven¦52285 days¦52286.
\v 34 Then¦52289 \add again\add* on the seventh¦52295 day¦52294, the priest will inspect it, and if the spot hasn't widened after being shaved and it doesn't seem to be more than skin deep, then¦52289 the priest can pronounce \add @that person\add* as ‘clean’ \add ≈once\add* they've washed their clothes¦52312.
\v 35 \add ≈However,\add* it¦52318 is did spread on their skin after¦52321 \add *that\add*,
\v 36 then the priest¦52325 must¦52324 inspect it again, and¦52324 if it's spread¦52327 then \add @that person\add* is ‘unclean¦52336’ (whether or not there's any yellow¦52335 hair¦52334).
\v 37 \add ≈But¦52339\add* if it seems that the spot \add ≈hasn't spread\add* and dark hair¦52344 is growing in it again, then¦52339 \add @that person's\add* \add ≈not infectious\add* and the priest¦52354 can pronounce them as ‘clean’.
\p
\v 38 If a man or woman¦52360 \add ≈finds very\add* white¦52369 spots on their¦52366 skin,
\v 39 then the priest¦52372 must¦52371 examine \add <them\add*. If the spots¦52377 on their¦52376 skin are dull white¦52379, then it's a skin rash that's broken¦52382 out and¦52373 they are ‘clean’.
\p
\v 40 If a man's head¦52391 has become¦52390 bare, then he's \add gone\add* bald and¦52388 is \add still\add* ‘clean’.
\v 41 \add ≈Similarly, \add* if the hair \add ≈is receding\add* from the front corners, he's \add ≈going bald\add* and¦52397 is \add still\add* ‘clean’.
\v 42 \add ≈However,\add* if there's a balding spot with a reddish-white infection, it's a skin disease¦52416 breaking¦52417 out via that¦52417 spot
\v 43 and¦52426 the priest¦52425 must¦52423 examine him. If it's a balding spot with a reddish-white infection that looks like a \add contagious\add* skin disease¦52436,
\v 44 then he's \add ≈contagious\add* and ‘unclean’. The priest¦52448 must¦52447 pronounce his as ‘unclean’ because of that infection on his head¦52449.
\p
\v 45 Anyone¦52452 who's developed an infectious skin disease¦52452 must tear their clothes¦52457 and \add ≈leave their hair loose\add*, and must \add ≈cover¦52466 their mouth\add* and call out, ‘Unclean, unclean.’
\v 46 They will remain ‘unclean’ as long as they \add still\add* have that¦52475 infection, and must¦52478 live alone¦52481 outside¦52483 the camp¦52484.
\s1 Regulations about moulds and fungi
\rem /s1 Laws concerning Mildew; Regulations About Mildew; Treatment of Contaminated Clothing
\p
\v 47 When a \add piece of\add* clothing has a mould growing on it, whether it's made of wool or linen¦52499,
\v 48 or whether it's something woven from wool or linen¦52505, or something made from leather,
\v 49 if the growth is greenish¦52517 or reddish¦52520 in colour, then¦52515 it's something that can spread and¦52515 it must¦52539 be shown¦52539 to the priest¦52542.
\v 50 The priest¦52545 must¦52544 examine the growth, and¦52549 quarantine the \add ≈article\add* for seven¦52553 days¦52554.
\v 51 On the seventh¦52561 day¦52560, if the growth has spread on that piece of material or leather equipment, and it's confirmed as spreadable and is ‘unclean¦52584’.
\v 52 \add ?@The owner\add* must burn¦52587 the piece of clothing or equipment that¦52610 contains the infection because¦52615 it's contagious, so it must be completely burnt¦52621 up.
\p
\v 53 \add ≈However\add* if the priest¦52625 notices that the growth hasn't spread¦52629 on the clothing or on the woven or leather \add ≈material\add*,
\v 54 then the priest¦52644 must¦52643 order that¦52647 the \add ≈material\add* be washed and¦52643 then quarantined for a \add ≈further\add* seven¦52652 days¦52654.
\v 55 \add On the seventh day,\add* the priest¦52658 must inspect that washed¦52661 \add ≈material\add*, and if the growth hasn't \add ≈changed its appearance\add*, even if it hasn't spread¦52676, then¦52657 it's ‘unclean¦52677’ and must be burnt in the fire¦52679—it's a mildew¦52681 that's on the front¦52685 or back of the material.
\v 56 \add ≈However,\add* if the priest¦52689 notices that the growth has faded after¦52693 being washed¦52694, then¦52687 it can be torn out of the clothing¦52700 or piece of leather or woven material.
\v 57 If it \add then\add* reappears on that clothing or material, then it's breaking¦52731 out, so then that article¦52728 must¦52716 be burnt in the fire¦52733.
\v 58 \add ≈On the other hand,\add* if the growth \add ≈vanished after being\add* washed, then it must¦52755 be washed a second¦52760 time and¦52741 then it will be ‘clean’.
\p
\v 59 \add @The above\add* are the regulations concerning any growth on a piece of woollen or linen¦52772 clothing¦52768 or fabric, or any leather article¦52780, to pronounce it ‘clean’ or ‘unclean¦52785’.
\c 14
\s1 Purification after a skin disease
\rem /s1 Purification after Having Skin Diseases; Cleansing from Skin Diseases; Purification of Lepers and Leprous Houses; Cleansing From Infectious Skin Diseases
\p
\v 1 Then Yahweh¦52789 told Mosheh¦52792:
\p
\v 2 These are the regulations for the purification¦52800 of a person who had a skin disease¦52798. They must¦52796 be taken to a priest¦52804\x + \xo 14:2: \xt Mat 8:4; Mrk 1:44; Luk 5:14; 17:14.\x*
\v 3 \add *who'll\add* go¦52806 outside¦52810 the camp¦52811 \add to meet them\add*. The priest¦52807 must¦52806 inspect \add that person\add*, and¦52806 if the skin disease has indeed left them,
\v 4 then¦52823 the priest¦52824 will order them to bring \add <him\add* two¦52827 live, ‘clean’ birds¦52829, some cedar¦52833 \add wood\add*, some scarlet¦52834 \add thread\add*, and¦52823 some hyssop¦52836 \add twigs\add*.
\v 5 The priest¦52839 must¦52838 tell \add @the person\add* to slaughter one bird \add ?≈so the blood runs into\add* a clay jug \add ?≈containing\add* water¦52852 \add ≈from a spring or creek\add*.
\v 6 Then \add @the priest\add* will take¦52859 the live bird, along with the cedar¦52864 wood, the scarlet¦52867 \add thread\add*, and the hyssop¦52871 \add twigs\add*, and dip them \add ≈all\add* into that¦52880 blood¦52878 of the slaughtered bird (\add ?≈mixed with\add* the \add ≈fresh\add* water¦52882),
\v 7 and \add ≈flick\add* it seven¦52891 times¦52892 onto the person who's being purified¦52887 from the skin disease¦52890. Then¦52885 \add @the priest\add* can pronounce them as ‘clean’ \add enough to re-enter the community\add*, and \add ≈release\add* the live bird \add to fly\add* into the countryside¦52902.
\v 8 The person who's being purified¦52905 must then wash their clothes¦52908, shave¦52909 all their hair¦52914, and¦52904 then bathe in \add flowing\add* water¦52916. After that, they can re-enter the camp¦52922 \add ≈but¦52904\add* must live outside¦52924 their tent¦52925 for seven¦52926 \add more\add* days¦52927.
\v 9 On the seventh¦52931 day¦52930, \add @that person\add* must¦52932 shave off all their hair (including¦52941 eyebrows¦52945 and beard¦52943 \add if appropriate\add*), wash their clothes¦52956 and bathe themself in \add flowing\add* water¦52961, then¦52929 they'll be ‘clean’.
\p
\v 10 Then¦52964 on the eighth¦52965 day¦52964, \add @that person\add* must¦52966 \add ≈get\add* two one-year-old \add male\add* lambs¦52969, and¦52964 one female lamb, \add all\add* \add ≈with no defects\add*, along with three¦52977 kilograms of fine flour¦52979 mixed¦52981 with oil as a grain¦52980 offering¦52980, as well as \add ≈half a litre\add* of \add olive\add* oil.
\v 11 \add That must¦52987 be taken to\add* the priest¦52988 who'd pronounced them as ‘clean’ \add ≈will accompany them\add* and¦52993 all those offerings to stand \add ≈in front¦52994\add* of Yahweh¦52995 at the entrance¦52996 to the \add ≈sacred¦52997\add* tent¦52997.
\v 12 Then¦53000 the priest¦53001 must¦53000 take one of the male lambs and the \add ≈container\add* of oil and present¦53006 it as a guilt¦53008 offering, then¦53000 he'll raise them as a wave offering \add ≈in front¦53016\add* of Yahweh¦53017.
\v 13 Then¦53019 \add @that person\add* must¦53019 slaughter that lamb¦53022 in the sacred place where¦53024 sin offerings and¦53019 burnt¦53031 offerings are slaughtered, because¦53034 this guilt¦53036 offering is like a sin offering in that it's for the priest¦53038—it's \add ≈very\add* sacred.
\v 14 Then¦53043 the priest¦53044 must¦53043 take¦53043 some of the blood¦53045 from that guilt¦53046 offering¦53046, and put it on the lobe of the right ear¦53052 of the person being purified¦53053, and on their right thumb¦53057 and right big¦53062 toe¦53062.
\v 15 Then¦53066 the priest¦53067 must¦53066 take¦53066 \add ≈the container\add* of olive oil¦53069 and¦53070 pour some into his left hand.
\v 16 Then¦53077 he'll dip his right¦53082 finger into that oil on his left palm, and¦53077 with that \add same\add* finger, \add ≈flick\add* it seven¦53096 times¦53097 \add ≈towards\add* Yahweh¦53099.
\v 17 Then¦53101 the priest¦53108 must¦53107 put some of the remaining¦53101 oil¦53102 on his palm¦53106 onto the lobe of the right ear¦53112 of the person being purified¦53113, and on their right thumb¦53117 and right big¦53122 toe¦53122—on top of the blood¦53126 from the guilt¦53127 offering¦53127.
\v 18 Then¦53129 the priest will put \add all\add* the remaining¦53129 oil¦53130 from his palm¦53134 onto the head¦53139 of the person being purified¦53140, and¦53141 the priest \add ≈will then¦53129 make that¦53131 person right with\add* Yahweh¦53145.
\p
\v 19 Then¦53147 the priest¦53148 must¦53147 make the sin offering and¦53147 \add ≈make that person right\add* after¦53157 being purified¦53155 from their ‘uncleanness¦53156’. After that \add ?@that person\add* will slaughter \add lamb for\add* the burnt¦53161 offering.
\v 20 Then¦53163 the priest¦53164 must¦53163 offer \add &that\add* burnt¦53167 offering and the grain¦53170 offering \add ≈on the fire\add* on the altar¦53171 and he will make \add ≈that person right again\add* and he will be ‘clean¦53175’.
\p
\v 21 \add ≈However,\add* if \add @that person\add* is poor and \add ≈cannot afford\add* \add the multiple lambs\add*, then they must¦53185 take \em one\em* lamb¦53186 to wave as the guilt¦53188 offering and to make \add ≈them right again\add*, along with \em one\em* kilogram of fine flour¦53193 mixed¦53195 with oil for the grain¦53197 offering, and the half litre of oil,
\v 22 plus¦53210 two doves or \add ≈young¦53205\add* pigeons—whichever¦53207 they can afford—one for a sin offering and¦53201 the other for the burnt¦53214 offering.
\v 23 Then¦53216 on \add &that\add* eighth¦53219 day¦53218, he'll take them to the priest¦53223 at the entrance¦53226 of the \add ≈sacred¦53227\add* tent¦53227 for purification¦53220 \add ≈in front¦53230\add* of Yahweh¦53231.
\v 24 Then¦53233 the priest¦53234 should take the guilt¦53238 offering lamb¦53237 and the \add ≈container\add* of oil and lift them up as a wave offering \add ≈in front¦53247\add* of Yahweh¦53248.
\v 25 Then¦53250 \add ?@the person\add* should slaughter \add &that\add* guilt offering lamb¦53253, and the priest¦53256 must¦53250 take some of \add ≈that\add* blood¦53257 and put it on the lobe of the right ear¦53263 of the person being purified¦53265, and on their right thumb¦53269 and right big toe.
\v 26 Then¦53278 \add *he\add* must¦53281 pour some of the oil¦53280 onto \add *his\add* left palm¦53285
\v 27 and¦53289 with his right¦53292 finger¦53291 he must¦53289 \add ≈flick\add* it seven¦53301 times¦53302 \add ≈towards\add* Yahweh¦53304.
\v 28 Then¦53306 the priest¦53307 must put some of the oil¦53310 from his palm¦53315 onto the lobe of the right ear¦53319 of the person being purified¦53320, and on their right thumb¦53324 and right big¦53329 toe¦53329—on top of the blood¦53335 from the guilt¦53336 offering¦53336.
\v 29 Then¦53338 the priest will put \add all\add* the remaining¦53338 oil¦53341 from his palm¦53345 onto the head¦53350 of the person being purified¦53351, and¦53338 the priest \add ≈will then¦53338 make that¦53342 person right with\add* Yahweh¦53355.
\v 30 Then¦53357 he must¦53357 \add ≈offer¦53357\add* one of the birds (dove¦53368 or pigeon—whatever \add @that person\add* \add ≈could afford\add*)
\v 31 as a sin offering and \add ≈the other\add* as a burnt¦53385 offering along with the grain¦53388 offering and he will make \add ≈that¦53374 person right again with\add* Yahweh¦53394.
\v 32 \add The above\add* are the regulations for anyone who has a skin disease¦53402 \add ≈but who couldn't afford the regular purification¦53408 offerings\add*.
\s1 Treating contaminated homes
\rem /s1 Cleansing From Mildew; Mildew in Houses; Treatment of Contaminated Houses
\p
\v 33 Then Yahweh¦53412 told Mosheh¦53415 and Aharon:
\p
\v 34 “\add ≈When\add* you enter into the land of Kanaan which¦53427 I'm giving you all as a possession, and if I \add ≈cause\add* an infection in one your¦53437 homes in \add *that\add* land,
\v 35 then¦53439 the homeowner must¦53439 go and¦53439 inform the priest¦53445 that something like an infection has appeared¦53448 in their house.
\v 36 The priest¦53453 must¦53452 order that everything be removed out of the house before¦53458 \add *he\add* comes to \add ≈inspect it\add* \add ≈so that\add* it won't¦53465 all be pronounced as ‘unclean¦53466’. After \add ≈that's done\add*, he'll go to see the house
\v 37 and \add ≈examine\add* the growth. If the growth is greenish¦53489 or reddish¦53491 and seems more than surface deep,
\v 38 then¦53498 the priest¦53499 must¦53498 leave the house via the \add main\add* entrance¦53505 and¦53498 quarantine the house for seven¦53511 days¦53512.
\v 39 On the seventh¦53517 day¦53516, the priest¦53515 must¦53514 return¦53514 and \add ≈examine it¦53520\add* \add again\add*, and if the growth has spread¦53520 on the house¦53523 walls¦53522,
\v 40 then¦53525 \add *he\add* must¦53525 order that those infected stones¦53530 be pulled out of the wall and¦53525 thrown¦53534 outside¦53538 the city¦53539 into a place¦53542 \add that's considered\add* ‘unclean¦53543’.
\v 41 Then¦53545 \add the homeowner\add* must¦53548 scrape¦53548 \add ≈all the plaster off the inside¦53549 walls\add* and¦53551 \add also\add* \add ≈dispose of that\add* at \add &that\add* ‘unclean¦53564’ place¦53563.
\v 42 Then¦53566 they \add ≈can replace the stones that were removed\add*, and¦53566 \add ≈apply fresh plaster¦53577\add* to the house¦53580.
\p
\v 43 \add ≈However,\add* if the growth returns¦53584 and breaks¦53586 out \add again\add* in the house \add even\add* after \add ≈the stones¦53592 were replaced and the walls were replastered\add*,
\v 44 then the priest¦53602 must¦53601 come \add back\add* and \add ≈reexamine\add* it. If the growth has spread¦53605 \add ≈on the walls\add*, then it's a malignant¦53609 growth and \add @the house\add* is ‘unclean¦53612’.
\v 45 \add @The owner\add* must tear the house down—its stones¦53621 and timber and all the mortar, must be \add ≈carted\add* outside¦53633 the city¦53634 into a place¦53637 \add that's considered\add* ‘unclean¦53638’.
\v 46 Any person that enters that house¦53643 \add ≈after the priest had quarantined it\add*, will be ‘unclean¦53649’ until¦53650 \add &that\add* evening¦53652.
\v 47 Any person who lies down or eats in that house, must¦53656 wash their clothes¦53659.
\p
\v 48 \add ≈However,\add* if the priest¦53671 \add ≈came back\add* after the house was replastered and¦53667 \add ≈after his inspection, find that\add* the growth \add ≈hasn't reappeared\add*, then¦53667 \add *he\add* can pronounce the house as ‘clean’ because¦53689 the \add ≈growth has gone\add*.
\v 49 Then he must¦53694 take¦53694 two¦53699 birds¦53700, cedar¦53702 wood, scarlet¦53703 \add ≈thread\add*, and some hyssop¦53705 \add twigs\add*,
\v 50 and¦53707 slaughter one bird \add ?≈so the blood runs into\add* a clay jug \add ?≈containing\add* water¦53719 \add ≈from a spring or creek\add*.
\v 51 Then¦53722 \add ?@the priest\add* must¦53722 take¦53722 the live bird, along with the cedar¦53727 wood, the scarlet¦53733 \add thread\add*, the hyssop¦53730 \add twigs\add* and the live bird, and dip them \add ≈all\add* into that¦53742 blood¦53740 of the slaughtered bird (\add ?≈mixed with\add* the \add ≈fresh\add* water¦53743), and \add ≈flick\add* it seven¦53749 times¦53750 onto the house¦53748.
\v 52 \add In that way,\add* he'll purify the house¦53755 with the bird's blood¦53756 and the \add ≈fresh\add* water¦53758, and with the live bird and the cedar¦53763 \add wood\add*, the hyssop¦53764 \add twigs\add* and the scarlet¦53765 \add thread\add*.
\v 53 Then¦53768 he must¦53768 \add ≈release\add* the live bird \add to fly\add* into the countryside¦53780, \add ≈thus\add* making the house¦53784 \add ≈right with God\add*, and¦53768 then¦53768 it'll be ‘clean’.
\p
\v 54 \add @The above\add* are the regulations concerning any serious¦53792 skin diseases¦53792 and¦53793 itchiness,
\v 55 as well as growths on clothing¦53796 and¦53797 \add ≈buildings\add*
\v 56 and swellings¦53799, rashes, and bright spots \add on the skin\add*,
\v 57 \add ≈so that you'll know how to determine what's\add* ‘unclean¦53805’ or ‘clean’. Those are the regulations for \add ≈infectious growths\add*.
\c 15
\s1 Dealing with bodily discharges
\rem /s1 Bodily Discharges; Unclean Bodily Discharges; Discharges Causing Uncleanness; Concerning Bodily Discharges
\p
\v 1 Then Yahweh¦53814 told Mosheh¦53817 and Aaron¦53820:
\p
\v 2 Tell¦53827 the \add ≈Israelis¦53826\add* that whenever any man has a discharge¦53834 from his \add ≈genitals\add*, then he becomes ‘unclean¦53837’.
\v 3 He becomes ‘unclean’ whether his body¦53845 secretes¦53844 the flow or if it's blocked—either way he's ‘unclean’.
\v 4 Any bed that¦53860 he was lying on during \add or after\add* the discharge¦53863 becomes ‘unclean’, as does anything he sits on.
\v 5 Anyone who touches¦53876 that bed must¦53876 wash their clothes¦53879 and bathe themself in water¦53881, and \add @that person\add* will be ‘unclean¦53882’ until¦53883 the evening¦53885.
\v 6 \add ≈Similarly,\add* anyone¦53887 who sits¦53887 on the place where he sat must¦53893 wash their clothes¦53897 and bathe themself in water¦53899, and \add @that person\add* will be ‘unclean¦53900’ until¦53901 the evening¦53903.
\v 7 Anyone¦53905 who touches¦53905 the man who had a discharge¦53907 must¦53908 wash their clothes¦53909 and bathe themself in water¦53911, and \add @that person\add* will be ‘unclean¦53912’ until¦53913 the evening¦53915.
\v 8 If that man who had a discharge¦53920 spits on some person who was ‘clean’, then¦53917 \add @that person\add* must¦53919 wash their clothes¦53923 and bathe themself in water¦53925, and they'll be ‘unclean¦53926’ until¦53927 the evening¦53929.
\v 9 Any thing that¦53934 the man who had a discharge¦53937 rides on, will become ‘unclean¦53938’,
\v 10 and anyone who touches¦53942 it¦53945 will be ‘unclean’ until the evening, plus¦53951 anyone who \add ≈carries¦53951 any of those things\add*, must¦53945 wash their clothes¦53954 and bathe themself in water¦53956, and they'll be ‘unclean’ until the evening.
\v 11 Anyone the \add ≈man who had a discharge¦53967\add* touches¦53964 and do didn't¦53969 rinse¦53971 their hands¦53968 in water, must¦53964 wash their clothes¦53974 and bathe themself in water, and they'll be ‘unclean¦53977’ until¦53978 the evening¦53980.
\v 12 Any container that¦53985 the \add ≈man who had a discharge¦53990\add* touches¦53987, must¦53987 be \add ≈smashed\add* if it's \add ≈made from\add* clay and¦53992 rinsed¦53997 with water¦53998 if it's \add ≈made from\add* wood.
\p
\v 13 When¦54000 the \add ≈man's discharge¦54003 ceases\add*, he must mark off seven¦54007 days¦54008 for his purification¦54009, and then¦54000 he must wash his clothes¦54011 and bathe himself in water¦54014, and \add after that,\add* he'll be ‘clean’.
\v 14 Then¦54018 on the eighth¦54019 day¦54018, he must¦54020 take¦54020 two doves or \add ≈young¦54027\add* pigeons, and¦54018 \add ≈stand in front¦54031\add* of Yahweh¦54032 at the entrance¦54035 to the \add ≈sacred¦54036\add* tent¦54036. There he should give¦54038 them to a priest¦54041,
\v 15 and the priest¦54045 must¦54043 \add ≈offer\add* one as a sin offering and \add ≈the other\add* as a burnt¦54049 offering, \add ≈thus making the man right\add* with Yahweh¦54054 for his discharge¦54055.
\p
\v 16 \add ≈Now\add* when a man¦54058 has an \add ≈emission of semen\add*, then he must¦54061 bathe his entire¦54070 body¦54072 in water¦54067, and he'll be ‘unclean¦54073’ until¦54074 the evening¦54076.
\v 17 He must¦54086 also wash all his clothing, and any leather articles on him \add ≈that came into contact with the semen\add* and \add @all of that\add* will be ‘unclean¦54093’ until¦54094 the evening¦54096.
\v 18 \add ≈When a man and a woman¦54099 ‘sleep together’\add*, then they must¦54101 both bathe in water¦54108, and they'll \add both\add* be ‘unclean’ until the evening.\f + \fr 15:18 \ft Note that if they had sexual relations in the evening, say 9pm, then they'd be ‘unclean’ all the next day and until the \+em following\+em* evening (because the Jewish ‘day’ begins after dusk—rather than at midnight like modern Western society counts time).\f*
\p
\v 19 When¦54114 a woman¦54114 \add ≈has her menstrual¦54126 period\add*, she'll be ‘unclean’ for seven¦54123 days¦54124, and¦54114 anyone¦54129 who touches¦54129 her \add ≈during that time¦54124\add* will be ‘unclean’ until¦54132 the evening¦54134.
\v 20 Anything that she lies on or sits on \add ≈during that time\add* will become ‘unclean’.
\v 21 Anyone¦54151 who touches¦54151 her¦54152 bed must¦54153 wash their clothes¦54154 and bathe in water¦54156, and they'll be ‘unclean¦54157’ until¦54158 the evening¦54160.
\v 22 Anyone¦54164 who touches¦54164 anything that¦54168 she¦54170 sat on must¦54170 wash their clothes¦54173 and bathe in water¦54175, and they'll be ‘unclean¦54176’ until¦54177 the evening¦54179,
\v 23 \add ≈i.e.,\add* whether it's her bed or something she¦54192 sat on, anyone who touches¦54196 it will be ‘unclean¦54199’ until¦54200 the evening¦54202.
\v 24 If a man¦54207 \add ≈sleeps with\add* \add @a menstruating¦54210 woman\add* and \add ≈gets blood\add* on him, then¦54204 he'll be ‘unclean’ for seven¦54213 days¦54214, and any bed that¦54218 he lies on will \add also\add* become ‘unclean’.
\p
\v 25 If any woman¦54225 \add ≈has a blood¦54230 flow when it's not her period\add*, or \add ≈keeps bleeding beyond her menstrual period\add*, all \add ≈those\add* days \add ≈will be regarded the same as her menstruation so she'll be\add* ‘unclean¦54248’.
\v 26 Any bed that¦54258 she lies on \add ≈as long as she's discharging¦54265 blood will be regarded the same as during her¦54264 menstruation and will\add* be ‘unclean¦54277’, as will anything she sits on.
\v 27 \add ≈Also¦54282,\add* any person who touches¦54284 them will be ‘unclean’ and they must¦54286 wash their clothes¦54288 and bathe in water¦54290, and they'll be ‘unclean’ until¦54292 the evening¦54294.
\v 28 \add ≈Once the flow stops,\add* then \add @the woman\add* must¦54300 count¦54300 off seven¦54302 days¦54303, and¦54296 then she'll be ‘clean’ after¦54304 that.
\v 29 Then¦54307 on the eighth¦54308 day¦54307, she must¦54309 take¦54309 two doves or \add ≈young¦54316\add* pigeons and¦54307 \add ≈give them\add* to a priest¦54322 at the entrance¦54325 to the \add ≈sacred¦54326\add* tent¦54326,
\v 30 and he will offer one as a sin offering and \add ≈the other\add* as a burnt¦54338 offering, \add ≈thus making her right with\add* Yahweh¦54343 from her ‘unclean¦54345’ flow.
\p
\v 31 You¦54352 two must¦54347 keep¦54347 the \add ≈Israeli¦54350 people¦54350\add* separate¦54347 from their ‘uncleanness¦54357’, then¦54347 they won't¦54354 defile my residence that's among¦54362 them, and¦54347 cause their \add own\add* death.
\p
\v 32 \add ≈The above\add* are the regulations for any man with a discharge¦54366 or a seminal emission that¦54367 makes him ‘unclean¦54373’,
\v 33 plus¦54379 any woman who is menstruating¦54377 or has a bodily discharge¦54379, as well as any man who sleeps with an ‘unclean¦54390’ woman.
\c 16
\s1 The day for making things right
\rem /s1 The Day of Atonement
\p
\v 1 Yahweh spoke¦54393 to Mosheh¦54397 after¦54398 the death¦54399 of two¦54400 of Aharon's sons¦54401 when they approached Yahweh \add wrongly\add* and died¦54407,
\v 2 and \add *he\add* told Mosheh¦54413:
\p Tell your brother¦54418 Aharon that if he doesn't \add want to\add* die¦54439, then¦54409 he mustn't \add just\add* enter the \add ≈holiest room¦54427\add* inside¦54428 the curtain¦54429 at any old time¦54424. The atonement lid is on the \add sacred¦54427\add* box, and I will appear¦54442 in a cloud¦54441 over \add *that\add* lid.\x + \xo 16:2: \xt Heb 6:19.\x*
\p
\v 3 This is \add how\add* Aharon must enter the \add ≈sacred¦54452 tent\add*: \add he must acquire\add* a \add ≈young¦54454\add* bull¦54453 for a sin offering, and a ram for a burnt¦54459 offering.
\v 4 ⇔He must bathe himself¦54475 in water¦54484 and then put on linen underclothes¦54466, followed by his sacred linen tunic¦54461 and tie the linen sash¦54473 around it. Then he must wrap the linen turban¦54476 on. Those are \add all\add* sacred clothes¦54479.
\p
\v 5 Then¦54493 \add @Aharon\add* must¦54494 \add acquire\add* two \add ≈young\add* goats for a sin offering and¦54490 one ram for a burnt¦54502 offering.
\v 6 \add *He\add* must¦54504 present¦54504 the bull¦54508 as a sin¦54509 offering¦54509 for himself¦54514 to \add ≈make both him and¦54504 his household¦54516 right with God¦54505\add*.
\v 7 Then¦54518 he must¦54518 take¦54518 the two¦54521 goats¦54522 and¦54518 make them stand \add ≈in front¦54525\add* of Yahweh¦54526 at the entrance¦54527 to the \add ≈sacred¦54528\add* tent¦54528,
\v 8 and \add ≈throw dice to decide which\add* one is for Yahweh¦54540, and one is to be the ‘scapegoat’.
\v 9 Then¦54545 Aharon¦54546 must¦54545 present¦54545 the goat¦54549 that's for Yahweh¦54554, and¦54545 offer it as a sin¦54556 offering¦54556,
\v 10 \add ≈but¦54558\add* the \add ≈chosen\add* ‘scapegoat’ must¦54564 be kept standing there \add ≈in front¦54567\add* of Yahweh, \add ≈because it'll be used to make the people right with Yahweh\add*, \add and¦54558 be sent\add* into the wilderness¦54574.
\p
\v 11 Then¦54576 Aharon must¦54576 present¦54576 the bull for his own sin offering \add ≈to make him and¦54576 his household¦54588 right with God\add*, then¦54576 he'll slaughter the bull for the sin offering for himself¦54586.
\v 12 Then¦54598 he must¦54598 get a panful of burning¦54604 coals¦54602 off the altar¦54606 \add ≈in front\add* of Yahweh¦54608 as well as two handfuls of finely-ground, fragrant incense¦54611, and¦54598 take¦54598 them inside¦54615 the curtain¦54616
\v 13 where he'll put the incense on the \add ≈coals\add* in Yahweh's¦54626 \add ≈presence\add*. Then¦54618 the \add smoke\add* cloud¦54629 from the incense will cover the atonement¦54633 lid on the \add sacred\add* chest, and¦54618 he won't¦54638 die.
\v 14 Then¦54641 he must take some of the bull's blood, and¦54641 using his finger, he must flick the blood seven¦54654 times¦54656 onto the eastern the side of the lid and seven times onto the front¦54648 of the lid.
\p
\v 15 Then¦54662 \add @Aharon\add* must¦54662 slaughter the goat for the people's¦54668 sin offering¦54666, and take its blood inside¦54675 the curtain¦54676, and do the same with it that¦54667 he did to the bull's blood—\add ≈flicking\add* it onto the side and front of the atonement lid,\x + \xo 16:15: \xt Heb 9:12.\x*
\v 16 \add ≈thus\add* making the \add ≈Israeli¦54698 people\add* \add ≈right with Yahweh\add* for their uncleanness and their \add ≈rebellion and disobedience\add*. \add ≈That's also for\add* the \add ≈sacred¦54696\add* tent which¦54708 is among \add @the people\add* with their uncleanness.
\v 17 \add ≈No one else can enter\add* the \add ≈sacred\add* tent¦54720 when \add @Aharon\add* enters to make atonement in the \add ≈sacred room¦54724\add* until¦54725 he leaves \add again\add*. He must¦54718 make atonement for himself¦54729 and¦54713 his household¦54731, as well as for the whole \add ≈Israeli¦54735 community\add*,
\v 18 then¦54738 he'll go out to the altar that's \add ≈in front¦54743\add* of Yahweh¦54745 and make atonement¦54746 for that—he must¦54738 take some of the bull's blood and some of the goat's blood and put it on the \add four\add* \add ≈projecting corners\add* of the altar.
\v 19 Then¦54760 he must¦54760 \add ≈flick\add* blood¦54764 on to it seven¦54766 times¦54767 with his finger¦54765, thus purifying¦54768 it and¦54760 \add ≈removing\add* the uncleanness¦54770 of the \add ≈Israeli¦54771 people¦54771 from it\add*.
\s1 The goat taking the blame
\rem /s1 The Scapegoat
\p
\v 20 \add ≈When¦54774\add* \add @Aharon\add* has finished¦54774 purifying the sacred \add ≈room¦54778\add*, the \add ≈sacred\add* tent¦54781, and¦54774 the altar¦54785, then¦54774 he should present¦54786 the live goat¦54789.
\v 21 \add *He\add* must place \add ≈both¦54796\add* his hands¦54797 on the goat's head, and confess¦54803 all of Israel's¦54811 \add ≈disobedience, rebellion, and shortcomings\add*—\add symbolically\add* placing them onto the goat's head, and then¦54792 he must choose a man \add ≈that's nearby\add* to take it into the wilderness¦54831.
\v 22 ⇔Then he'll release the goat there in the wilderness¦54849, and¦54833 the goat will carry all their¦54840 sins into that barren land.
\p
\v 23 Then¦54851 Aharon¦54852 must¦54851 enter the \add ≈sacred\add* tent¦54855 and take off the linen¦54861 garment¦54860 that¦54862 he'd put on as he'd entered into the sacred \add ≈room¦54867\add* and leave¦54868 them there¦54869.\x + \xo 16:23: \xt Eze 44:19.\x*
\v 24 Then¦54871 he must¦54871 wash himself in water¦54875 in a sacred¦54877 place¦54876, put on his \add regular\add* clothes¦54881, and go out and make his burnt offering and the burnt offering for the people, \add ≈thus making both himself and the people right with Yahweh\add*.
\v 25 Then¦54896 he must¦54899 burn the fat from the sin¦54898 offering¦54898 up on the altar¦54900.
\v 26 \add ≈Also¦54902,\add* the person who led away the ‘scapegoat’ must¦54907 wash his clothes¦54908 and bathe himself in water¦54913, and then¦54902 he can reenter the camp¦54920.
\v 27 Then¦54922 \add the remains of\add* the bull¦54923 and the goat¦54927 from the sin offerings (whose blood¦54933 was taken into the sacred \add ≈room¦54935\add* to make atonement¦54934) must be taken to a place¦54935 outside¦54939 the camp¦54940 where they must be burnt—skins, flesh¦54948, and dung.\x + \xo 16:27: \xt Heb 13:11.\x*
\v 28 The man who burnt them must¦54955 then wash his clothes¦54956 and bathe his body¦54960 in water¦54961, and then he can reenter the camp¦54968.
\s1 The national purification day
\rem /s1 Observing the Day of Atonement
\p
\v 29 This will be a permanent¦54973 regulation¦54972 for you all:
\p On the 10th of the seventh¦54975 month \add (of Tishrei—around September/October)\add*, all of you including¦54982 those who are native-born as well as foreigners living among¦54990 you, must¦54970 humble yourselves and¦54970 not \add ≈work¦54984 that day\add*\x + \xo 16:29-34: \xt Lev 23:26-32; Num 29:7-11.\x*
\v 30 because on that day¦54994, \add @the high priest\add* will purify¦54998 you all from your sins¦55001 \add ≈to make you right with\add* Yahweh¦55003, and you'll be ‘clean’.
\v 31 It'll be a \add ≈very sacred\add* rest day for you, and¦55010 you all must¦55010 humble \add ≈yourselves\add*—a permanent¦55015 regulation¦55014 \add for you all\add*.
\v 32 The priest \add ≈who's anointed¦55021 and ordained to succeed\add* his father¦55030 \add as high priest\add* must \add ≈be the one to\add* make atonement¦55017, and he must be wearing his \add ≈sacred¦55037\add* linen¦55035 clothes¦55034.
\v 33 He will \add first\add* \add ≈purify\add* the \add ≈sacred room\add* and the \add ≈sacred\add* tent¦55046, and the altar¦55050, and then¦55039 \add ≈make all the priests¦55053 right with Yahweh\add* and \add finally,\add* the \add ≈entire¦55056 community\add*.
\v 34 That will become¦55062 a permanent¦55067 regulation¦55066 every year¦55077 to \add ≈make all the Israelis¦55071 right with Yahweh because of\add* their¦55075 sins¦55075.
\p \add ≈So¦55062\add* Mosheh¦55084 did exactly as Yahweh had instructed¦55080 him.
\c 17
\s1 Slaughtering animals
\rem /s1 The Slaughtering of Animals; Law of holiness; Prohibitions against Eating Blood; The Sacredness of Blood; Eating Blood Forbidden
\p
\v 1 Then Yahweh¦55088 told Mosheh¦55091:
\p
\v 2 Tell Aharon and his sons¦55100 and all the \add ≈Israelis¦55104\add* that¦55110 \add ≈these are the instructions¦55112 from\add* Yahweh¦55113:
\v 3 \add ≈No Israeli¦55119 is allowed to\add* slaughter a bull¦55122 or lamb or goat \add either\add* inside the camp or outside¦55133 \add *it\add*.
\v 4 \add ≈If¦55148 they're not taken\add* to the entrance¦55138 to the \add ≈sacred¦55139\add* tent¦55147 to be presented as an offering to Yahweh¦55145 \add ≈in front¦55146\add* of \add *his\add* residence, then¦55136 that person¦55151 \add ≈will be held guilty\add* of its blood—they've shed blood so they must¦55150 be cut off from his people¦55159.
\v 5 The \add ≈Israelis¦55164\add* \add ≈must stop\add* sacrificing their¦55168 \add ≈animals\add* in the countryside¦55175, and \add instead\add* bring them to Yahweh at the entrance¦55180 to the \add ≈sacred¦55181\add* tent¦55181, \add i.e., they must\add* bring them to the priest¦55185 and sacrifice them as peace¦55188 offerings¦55188 to Yahweh.
\v 6 Then¦55192 the priest¦55193 will splash the blood¦55196 onto Yahweh's¦55200 altar¦55199 at the tent¦55202 entrance¦55201, and¦55204 burn up the fat to become a \add ≈soothing¦55207 aroma¦55206\add* for Yahweh.
\v 7 Then¦55210 they \add ≈won't¦55210 be able to continue offering\add* their sacrifices¦55212 to the goat demons that¦55218 they're prostituting¦55220 themselves¦55220 to. \add ≈The above\add* will be a permanent¦55223 regulation¦55222 \add ≈throughout\add* the generations¦55228.
\p
\v 8 You must¦55231 tell them that if an \add ≈Israeli¦55235\add* or a foreigner living among¦55242 them, makes a burnt¦55246 offering¦55246 or sacrifice¦55249
\v 9 without bringing¦55257 it to Yahweh¦55260 at the \add ≈sacred¦55254\add* tent¦55254 entrance¦55253, then¦55251 that person must¦55257 be cut off from \add ≈the community\add*.
\s1 The law concerning the blood
\rem /s1 Eating Blood Prohibited
\p
\v 10 \add If¦55287 there's\add* any \add ≈Israeli¦55269\add* or foreigner living among¦55274 them, who eats blood, then¦55266 I'll¦55280 \add ≈oppose\add* that person and¦55266 remove them from \add ≈the community\add*\x + \xo 17:10: \xt Gen 9:4; Lev 7:26-27; 19:26; Deu 12:16,23; 15:23.\x*
\v 11 because the body's life is in the blood. I myself have given¦55298 you \add @blood\add* to make atonement for your lives at the altar¦55302, because \add ≈it's the blood that¦55311 can atone for\add* life.\x + \xo 17:11: \xt Heb 9:22.\x*
\v 12 \add ≈That's why\add* I told the \add ≈Israelis¦55318\add* that none of them must¦55326 eat blood—\add not even\add* the foreigners that live among¦55330 them may eat blood.
\p
\v 13 \add ≈So any person\add* (\add ≈Israeli¦55340\add* or foreigner living among¦55345 them) who catches wild game (\add ≈including¦55337\add* birds) to eat, they must¦55347 pour its blood¦55358 out and cover¦55359 it with soil
\v 14 because the life of \add ≈their bodies\add* is the blood that's in them. \add ≈Again¦55373,\add* \add that's why\add* I've¦55371 told the \add ≈Israelis¦55372\add* not to eat the blood of any \add ≈living thing\add* because the life is in the blood, and anyone who eats it must¦55390 be cut off \add ≡from the community\add*.
\p
\v 15 Anyone who eats \add part of\add* a carcass¦55397 \add they found\add* or one that was \add ≈killed by wild animals¦55398\add*, must¦55396 wash their clothes¦55402 and bathe in water¦55404, and they'll be ‘unclean¦55405’ until¦55406 the evening¦55408, and then¦55392 they'll be ‘clean’ \add again\add*.
\v 16 \add ≈However,\add* if \add @that person\add* doesn't wash \add their clothes\add* or bathe, then¦55411 they must¦55413 bear \add the punishment for\add* their own \add ≈disobedience\add*.
\c 18
\s1 Sexual relationships
\rem /s1 Unlawful Sexual Relations; Forbidden Sexual Practices; Sexual Relations
\p
\v 1 Then Yahweh¦55422 told Mosheh¦55425:
\p
\v 2 Tell the \add ≈Israeli¦55431\add* that I am their god¦55437 Yahweh¦55436.
\v 3 \add ≈They mustn't behave as if they're still there¦55457 in\add* Egypt¦55442, nor should they \add ≈behave like the Canaanites that were living\add* in the land that I'm taking you all into, and don't¦55447 \add ≈emulate their¦55460 customs and practices\add*.
\v 4 You all must¦55467 \add ≈imbibe my values and¦55468 follow my instructions¦55470\add*. I am your god¦55476 Yahweh¦55475.
\v 5 You all must¦55478 \add ≈follow my instructions¦55481 and¦55478 my values\add*—those who do¦55486 so will live¦55489. I am your god Yahweh¦55492.\x + \xo 18:5: \xt Neh 9:29; Eze 18:9; 20:11-13; Luk 10:28; Rom 10:5; Gal 3:12.\x*
\p
\v 6 None of you may \add ≈ever flirt with any close relative¦55501 to try to get them to undress\add*. I am Yahweh¦55508.
\v 7 You¦55512 must¦55512 \add ≈never mess with your father's naked body\add*, or your mother's—no, she's your mother so don't¦55515 \add ≈ever take advantage of her¦55521 nakedness\add*.
\v 8 Don't¦55528 \add ≈ever mess with any of your father's wives, because their naked bodies are the realm\add* of your father.\x + \xo 18:8: \xt Lev 20:11; Deu 22:30; 27:20.\x*
\v 9 Don't¦55539 \add ≈flirt with your sister's nakedness, whether she's a full sister, a half sister, or an adopted sister\add*.\x + \xo 18:9: \xt Lev 20:17; Deu 27:22.\x*
\v 10 Don't¦55562 \add ≈flirt with your grandchildren's nakedness, because¦55565 you'd be absolutely shaming yourself\add*.
\v 11 Don't¦55579 \add ≈flirt with your step-sister's\add* nakedness, because she's your sister and her¦55581 nakedness \add ≈isn't¦55579 yours to enjoy\add*.
\v 12 Don't¦55588 \add ≈flirt with your aunts nakedness¦55584 on your father's side\add*, because \add ≈she's closely related¦55590 to\add* your father.\x + \xo 18:12-14: \xt Lev 20:19-20.\x*
\v 13 Don't¦55599 \add ≈flirt with your aunt's nakedness¦55595 on your mother's side\add*, because¦55601 \add ≈she's closely related¦55603 to\add* your mother.
\v 14 Don't¦55611 \add ≈flirt with your uncle's nakedness¦55608 on your father's side\add*, and \add ≈keep away\add* from his wife, because she's your aunt.
\v 15 Don't¦55625 \add ≈flirt with\add* your daughter-in-law's nakedness, because she's your son's wife¦55627 and her¦55632 nakedness \add ≈isn't¦55625 yours to enjoy\add*.\x + \xo 18:15: \xt Lev 20:12.\x*
\v 16 Don't¦55639 \add ≈flirt with\add* your sister-in-law, because \add ≈her naked body is the realm\add* of your brother.\x + \xo 18:16: \xt Lev 20:21.\x*
\v 17 Don't¦55649 \add ≈flirt with\add* the nakedness of \add both\add* a woman¦55647 and her daughter \add ≈or her granddaughter\add*, because they're \add ≈related¦55665 to each other\add*—that would be perverse.\x + \xo 18:17: \xt Lev 20:14; Deu 27:23.\x*
\v 18 Don't¦55674 take your wife's sister¦55673 \add ≈to be a junior wife\add* \add ≈while your wife is still alive\add*.
\p
\v 19 Don't¦55687 approach a woman¦55684 \add ≈who's menstruating¦55685, to undress her¦55685\add*, because she's ‘unclean¦55686’.\x + \xo 18:19: \xt Lev 20:18.\x*
\v 20 Don't¦55696 sleep with \add ≈someone else's\add* wife¦55694—your \add ≈child with her¦55703 would be\add* ‘unclean¦55701’.\x + \xo 18:20: \xt Lev 20:10.\x*
\v 21 Don't¦55706 \add ≈sacrifice your children\add* to Molek¦55710 so you don't¦55706 profane¦55712 your god's \add ≈reputation¦55715\add*. I¦55717 am Yahweh¦55718.\x + \xo 18:21: \xt Lev 20:1-5.\x*
\v 22 Don't¦55723 \add ≈have sexual relations\add* with a man like with a woman¦55726—it's an abomination¦55727.\x + \xo 18:22: \xt Lev 20:13.\x*
\v 23 \add Men,\add* don't \add ≈have sexual relations\add* with any animal as that would make you¦55735 ‘unclean¦55737’. And women, don't give¦55735 yourself \add ≈sexually\add* to any animal as that's perverse.\x + \xo 18:23: \xt Exo 22:19; Lev 20:15-16; Deu 27:21.\x*
\p
\v 24 Don't¦55750 make yourselves¦55752 ‘unclean’ in any of \add @the above\add* ways, because¦55756 all of those things were done by the \add ≈people groups\add* that¦55762 I'm¦55764 \add ≈driving out\add* of this land ahead of you all.
\v 25 The land had become ‘unclean¦55768’ \add ≈so I made them pay for their wickedness\add* and¦55768 \add so\add* the land will vomit¦55773 out its inhabitants¦55777.
\v 26 \add ≈However,\add* you all must¦55779 \add ≈obey my instructions¦55783 and decisions¦55783\add* and not \add ≈tolerate\add* any of \add ≈that perverse behaviour\add*—not you who are native-born, nor any foreigner living among¦55795 you all,
\v 27 because all \add ≈that perversity\add* was done by those living there before¦55809 you all, and the land became¦55810 ‘unclean¦55810’.
\v 28 \add Don't¦55813 think\add* that the land won't¦55813 vomit¦55815 you all out just like it's doing to the \add ≈people groups\add* that have been \add there\add* before¦55826 you,
\v 29 because everyone¦55829 who does any of \add ≈those perversities\add* will be cut off from their¦55840 \add ≈community\add*.
\v 30 \add ≈So¦55842\add* you all must¦55842 carefully guard against \add ≈practising any of those detestable customs¦55848\add* which were \add ≈previously\add* done¦55851 \add there\add* and¦55842 which would make you all ‘unclean¦55854’. I¦55856 am your god¦55858 Yahweh¦55857.
\c 19
\s1 Various moral imperatives
\rem /s1 Ritual and Moral Holiness; Various Laws; Laws of Holiness and Justice; Holiness in Personal Conduct
\p
\v 1 Then Yahweh¦55862 told Mosheh¦55865:
\p
\v 2 Tell the \add ≈entire¦55871 Israeli¦55874 community\add* that they must¦55877 \add ≈be separate from others\add*, because¦55881 I, your god¦55885 Yahweh¦55884, am holy \add (i.e., separated from impurity)\add*.\x + \xo 19:2: \xt Lev 11:44-45; 1Pe 1:16.\x*
\v 3 Everyone must¦55890 \add ≈respect and obey\add* their \add ≈parents\add*, and observe my rest days. I am your god¦55897 Yahweh¦55896.\x + \xo 19:3: a \xt Exo 20:12; Deu 5:16; \xo b \xt Exo 20:8; Deu 5:12.\x*
\p
\v 4 Don't¦55899 turn¦55901 to worthless¦55904 idols¦55904, and¦55905 don't¦55899 make cast metal¦55906 gods¦55905 for yourselves. I¦55910 am your god¦55912 Yahweh¦55911.\x + \xo 19:4: a \xt Lev 26:1; \xo b \xt Exo 20:23; 34:17; Deu 27:15.\x*
\p
\v 5 When¦55918 you all sacrifice peace¦55917 offerings¦55917, \add ≈do it¦55920 correctly so that you'll all be accepted¦55919\add*.
\v 6 \add The meat from\add* your sacrifice¦55923 must be eaten¦55924 that same day or the next day—anything left until¦55927 the third¦55930 day must be \add ≈thrown into the fire\add*.
\v 7 If it was to be eaten on the third¦55938 day¦55937, it would be ‘unclean¦55939’ and¦55934 not acceptable¦55942,
\v 8 and the people eating it would have to bear their own \add ≈guilt\add* for profaning¦55953 Yahweh's¦55952 holiness, and that person must¦55946 be cut off from \add ≈the community\add*.
\p
\v 9 When¦55959 you all harvest your \add ≈crops off\add* your land, you mustn't \add ≈cut the grain right to the very\add* edge of your field¦55967, and¦55959 nor \add ≈can you all pick up any dropped stalks\add*.\x + \xo 19:9-10: \xt Lev 27:15; Deu 24:19-22.\x*
\v 10 In your \add #vineyards\add*, you must not \add ≈pick every last grape¦55977 or pick up any that fall on the ground\add*, because they must be left for the poor and¦55974 for the foreigners. I am your god¦55987 Yahweh¦55986.
\p
\v 11 You all mustn't steal¦55990 or deceive¦55993, or defraud any fellow¦55998 citizen¦55998,\x + \xo 19:11: a \xt Exo 20:15; Deu 5:19; \xo b \xt Exo 20:16; Deu 5:20.\x*
\v 12 and don't¦56000 use my name to \add ≈seal\add* a promise and then¦56000 \add go ahead and\add* \add ≈ruin my reputation¦56003\add*. I¦56010 am Yahweh¦56011.\x + \xo 19:12: \xt Exo 20:7; Deu 5:11; Mat 5:33.\x*
\p
\v 13 Don't oppress¦56015 your¦56018 \add #neighbours\add* or steal from them. Don't \add ≈fail to pay a day-labourer as they finish each day's work\add*.\x + \xo 19:13: \xt Deu 24:14-15.\x*
\v 14 Don't¦56037 curse¦56033 a deaf person, or \add ≈put something in front of\add* a blind¦56036 person \add to trip them\add*. You must¦56033 \add ≈respect and obey\add* your god¦56041. I am Yahweh¦56043.\x + \xo 19:14: \xt Deu 27:18.\x*
\p
\v 15 Don't¦56050 judge unfairly—showing partiality to the poor, or honouring¦56057 those who are well-known—you must¦56047 \add always\add* judge your fellow¦56062 citizens¦56062 fairly.\x + \xo 19:15: \xt Exo 23:6-8; Deu 16:19.\x*
\v 16 Don't go¦56066 around slandering¦56067 people. Don't \add ?≈take advantage of your¦56074 neighbour's¦56074 death\add*. I am Yahweh¦56076.
\p
\v 17 You mustn't hate¦56080 your brother¦56083. Certainly rebuke \add ≈those you interact with\add* \add ≈so you don't¦56090 get blamed for their bad behaviour\add*.\x + \xo 19:17: \xt Mat 18:15.\x*
\v 18 Don't¦56099 try to get revenge against others or hold a grudge against any of your people¦56105, but¦56099 \add instead,\add* love¦56106 your neighbour¦56107 as yourself. I¦56109 am Yahweh¦56110.\x + \xo 19:18: \xt Mat 5:43; 19:19; 22:39; Mrk 12:31; Luk 10:27; Rom 13:9; Gal 5:14; Jam 2:8.\x*
\p
\v 19 \add ≈Follow my instructions¦56114\add*—don't crossbreed two different kinds of animals, don't sow two different crops in your field¦56121, and don't wear clothing¦56126 made of different kinds of thread.\x + \xo 19:19: \xt Deu 22:9-11.\x*
\p
\v 20 If a man impregnates a woman¦56140 who's destined to be someone else's slave¦56145 and she hasn't been freed, compensation¦56157 needs to be \add paid\add*.\f + \fr 19:20 \ft We as modern readers don't understand all the dynamics of this seemingly complex social situation.\f* They mustn't be executed, because¦56135 she hadn't been freed.
\v 21 \add ≈However,\add* \add @that man\add* must¦56166 take a ram to Yahweh¦56170 at the \add ≈sacred¦56174\add* tent's entrance¦56173 for a guilt offering,
\v 22 and the priest¦56181 will make \add ≈him right with\add* Yahweh¦56185 by means of that¦56189 guilt¦56183 offering¦56183 ram, and then¦56179 he'll be forgiven¦56191 for his transgression.
\p
\v 23 When you all enter into the land and plant¦56204 various kinds of fruit trees, you mustn't eat the fruit for the first three¦56214 years¦56215—it should be \add regarded as\add* ‘uncircumcised¦56218’ \add for that duration\add*.
\v 24 Then¦56222 in the fourth¦56223 year¦56222, all that fruit¦56227 must¦56224 be \add regarded as\add* ‘sacred¦56228’—praise¦56229 offerings¦56229 for Yahweh¦56230.
\v 25 \add ≈Finally,\add* in the fifth¦56233 year¦56232, you can eat¦56234 that fruit¦56237 and¦56232 add that produce¦56240 to your harvest. I am your god¦56243 Yahweh¦56242.
\p
\v 26 Don't eat¦56246 anything with the blood¦56249 \add still in it\add*. Don't practice divination¦56251 or witchcraft.\x + \xo 19:26: a \xt Gen 9:4; Lev 7:26-27; 17:10-14; Deu 12:16,23; 15:23; \xo b \xt Deu 18:10.\x*
\v 27 Don't¦56259 \add have haircuts that\add* round¦56256 off your hair at the sides, and \add men\add*, don't¦56259 trim the edges of your \add #beards\add*.\x + \xo 19:27-28: \xt Lev 21:5; Deu 14:1.\x*
\v 28 Don't¦56267 make cuts on your¦56269 bodies \add ≈when someone dies¦56266\add*, and¦56270 don't¦56267 \add ≈tattoo¦56270\add* yourselves¦56274. I¦56275 am Yahweh¦56276.
\p
\v 29 don't¦56278 defile your¦56283 daughter¦56283 by making¦56284 her¦56284 prostitute herself¦56284, \add ≈so the country\add* doesn't prostitute itself¦56287 and become full of wickedness¦56291.\x + \xo 19:29: \xt Deu 23:17.\x*
\v 30 Keep my rest days, and¦56297 \add ≈respect\add* my sanctuary¦56297. I am Yahweh¦56300.\x + \xo 19:30: \xt Lev 26:2.\x*
\p
\v 31 Don't¦56302 turn¦56304 to mediums and¦56308 diviners—don't¦56302 make yourselves ‘unclean¦56314’ by means of them. I¦56316 am your god¦56318 Yahweh¦56317.\x + \xo 19:31: \xt Deu 18:11; 1Sam 28:3; 2Ki 23:4; Isa 8:19.\x*
\p
\v 32 Stand up for those with gray hair¦56321, and honour¦56323 the \add ≈presence\add* of the elderly. \add ≈Honour and respect\add* your¦56327 god¦56327. I am Yahweh¦56329.
\p
\v 33 ⇔Don't \add ≈take advantage of\add* \add #foreigners\add* when they stay in your¦56337 land—\x + \xo 19:33-34: \xt Exo 22:21; Deu 24:17-18; 27:19.\x*
\v 34 you all must¦56344 treat \add #foreigners\add* the same as native-born \add Israelis\add* and love them like you \add ≡love\add* yourselves¦56352, because¦56353 you were all foreigners in Egypt¦56358 \add (Heb. Mitsrayim)\add*. I am your god¦56361 Yahweh¦56360.
\p
\v 35 Don't allow injustice¦56366 \add either\add* in \add ≈judging cases\add*, \add or by trading with rigged\add* weights¦56369 and¦56370 measures¦56368—\x + \xo 19:35-36: \xt Deu 25:13-16; Prv 20:10; Eze 45:10.\x*
\v 36 your scales and weights¦56374 and measuring containers must¦56381 be honest. I am your god¦56385 Yahweh¦56384 who brought¦56388 you all out of Egypt¦56391 \add (Heb. Mitsrayim)\add*.
\v 37 You all must¦56393 \add ≈obey my instructions¦56398 and decisions¦56403\add* and \add ≈stick to\add* them. I am Yahweh¦56407.
\c 20
\s1 Penalties for disobedience
\rem /s1 Penalties for Violations of Holiness; Punishments for Sin; Penalties for Disobedience; Punishments for Disobedience
\p
\v 1 Then Yahweh¦56411 told Mosheh¦56414:
\p
\v 2 Tell the \add ≈Israeli¦56419 people\add* that if any of them, or any foreigner staying in Yisrael¦56420, gives any of their \add ≈children\add* to Molek¦56436, then¦56417 \add *that person\add* must \add ≈definitely be executed\add*—the people must do it by throwing rocks¦56441 at them.
\v 3 \add Yes,\add* I myself will \add ≈personally punish\add* that person¦56449 and¦56444 cut them off from the people¦56454 for giving their \add ≈child\add* to Molek¦56458 and so making my sanctuary¦56463 ‘unclean¦56460’ and profaning¦56464 my sacred¦56468 name¦56467.
\v 4 If the people¦56473 of the land \add just\add* hides their eyes¦56477 from \add seeing\add* anyone¦56483 offering their \add ≈child\add* to Molek¦56484 so they¦56472 don't¦56485 have to execute \add @that person\add*,
\v 5 then¦56489 I'll \add also\add* remove that \add other\add* person¦56494 and¦56489 their clan. I'll cut them off from their people¦56509, along with anyone else who practises prostitution by prostituting themselves to Molek¦56507.
\p
\v 6 I'll \add ≈take action against\add* any person who turns to mediums or diviners to prostitute¦56520 themselves to them, and¦56511 I'll cut them off from their people¦56531.
\v 7 You must¦56533 keep¦56533 yourselves¦56533 \add ≈separate from those kinds of things to be\add* holy, because¦56536 I, Yahweh¦56538, am your god¦56539.
\v 8 You all must¦56541 \add ≈follow my instructions¦56544\add* and¦56545 \add ≈implement\add* them. I am Yahweh¦56548 who \add ≈makes you different from other people groups\add*.
\p
\v 9 Any person who curses¦56556 their father or mother must¦56556 be \add ≈executed\add*—their blood¦56568 will be on \add @their own head\add* for cursing their \add ≈parents\add*.\x + \xo 20:9: \xt Exo 21:17; Mat 15:4; Mrk 7:10.\x*
\p
\v 10 Any man who commits adultery¦56587 with another man's wife, maybe even his neighbours¦56583 wife, must¦56573 be \add ≈executed\add*—both the \add ≈man and¦56571 the woman\add*.\x + \xo 20:10: \xt Exo 20:14; Lev 18:20; Deu 5:18.\x*
\v 11 Any man¦56590 who sleeps with any of his father's wives, has exposed¦56599 his father's nakedness¦56597. Both of them must¦56592 be \add ≈executed\add*—their blood¦56604 is on \add @their own heads\add*.\x + \xo 20:11: \xt Lev 18:8; Deu 22:30; 27:20.\x*
\v 12 If a man¦56607 sleeps with his daughter-in-law, both of them must¦56609 be executed. That's perversion and¦56607 so their blood¦56618 is on \add @their own heads\add*.\x + \xo 20:12: \xt Lev 18:15.\x*
\v 13 If a man \add ≈has a sexual relationship\add* with another man, both of them have done something detestable and¦56621 both of them must¦56623 be executed—their blood¦56634 is on \add @their own heads\add*.\x + \xo 20:13: \xt Lev 18:22.\x*
\v 14 If a man takes both a mother¦56645 and¦56637 her¦56645 daughter as wives, then¦56637 that's wicked. They must¦56639 all be burnt \add ≈to death\add* so that depravity won't¦56652 \add take root\add* among¦56656 you.
\p
\v 15 If a man \add tries to\add* \add ≈have sex with\add* an animal, that man must be executed and¦56658 the animal must \add also\add* be killed.\x + \xo 20:15-16: \xt Exo 22:19; Lev 18:23; Deu 27:21.\x*
\v 16 If a woman \add ≈presents herself sexually\add* to any animal, you must¦56672 \add ≈execute\add* the woman and¦56670 kill the animal—their blood¦56689 is on \add @their own heads\add*.
\p
\v 17 If a man¦56692 \add ?≈sleeps with\add* his sister (whether on his father's¦56701 or mother's¦56705 side) and they see each other's nakedness, it's a disgrace and they must be cut off from their¦56721 people¦56721—he's exposed¦56724 her¦56709 nakedness and he must bear his wickedness.\x + \xo 20:17: \xt Lev 18:9; Deu 27:22.\x*
\v 18 If a man \add ≈sleeps\add* with a woman¦56734 who's menstruating¦56735, he's exposed¦56745 her nakedness¦56739 and¦56728 uncovered¦56736 the \add ≈source\add* of her blood¦56749, \add so\add* they must¦56731 both be cut off from among their¦56753 people¦56753.\x + \xo 20:18: \xt Lev 18:19.\x*
\p
\v 19 You mustn't expose the nakedness¦56755 of your sister (whether on your father's side or mother's¦56757 side) because¦56762 \add that's like\add* exposing your own \add ≈body\add*. They must¦56759 bear their¦56767 wickedness.\x + \xo 20:19-20: \xt Lev 18:12-14.\x*
\v 20 A man¦56770 who \add ≈sleeps\add* with his aunt, he's exposed¦56778 his uncle's¦56777 nakedness¦56776. They'll bear their¦56779 wickedness \add by\add* dying childless¦56781.
\v 21 If a man \add ?≈marries\add* his brother's wife, it's \add ≈indecent\add*. He's exposed¦56795 his nakedness¦56793 \add and¦56784\add* they'll be childless¦56796.\x + \xo 20:21: \xt Lev 18:16.\x*
\p
\v 22 You all must¦56799 \add ≈obey my instructions¦56804 and decisions¦56809\add* and \add ≈stick to\add* them, and then¦56799 the land that I'm about¦56819 to take you into, won't¦56812 vomit¦56814 you all out.
\v 23 Don't¦56825 follow the \add ≈customs\add* of the \add #peoples\add* that¦56829 I'll drive out ahead of you all, because¦56834 they¦56840 do all of \add @the above\add* things, and¦56841 I detest them
\v 24 and I've¦56844 told you all that you yourselves will inherit their¦56850 land—I'll¦56852 give¦56852 it to you \add ≈to take possession of\add*. It's a land flowing¦56857 with milk¦56858 and honey¦56859. I am your god¦56862 Yahweh¦56861 who separates¦56865 you all from the \add other\add* people¦56869 \add groups\add*.
\v 25 You all must¦56871 \add ≈distinguish\add* between ‘clean’ and ‘unclean’ animals and birds. Don't¦56882 make yourselves detestable¦56884 \add to me\add* with any animal or bird or crawling creature which¦56894 I've¦56896 distinguished for you all as ‘unclean’.
\v 26 You all must¦56900 be ‘holy’ to me, because¦56903 I Yahweh¦56906 am holy, and¦56907 I've¦56907 set you all apart from the other \add ≈people¦56911 groups\add* to be mine.
\p
\v 27 Any man or woman¦56918 who's a medium or diviner must be executed—the people¦56929 must do it by throwing rocks¦56929 at them.
\c 21
\s1 Stricter instructions for priests
\rem /s1 The Holiness of the Priests; Instructions for the Priests; Rules for Priests; The Holiness of Priests
\p
\v 1 Then Yahweh¦56936 told Mosheh¦56939:
\p Tell Aharon's descendants the priests¦56943 that they must¦56946 not defile themselves among¦56952 the \add ≈Israelis\add*, by touching anything that's not living¦56948
\v 2 apart from the body of a close relative¦56957 like a \add ≈parent, child,\add* brother¦56964
\v 3 or \add ≈unmarried\add* sister¦56966—the priest can become ‘unclean¦56976’ by means of one of them.
\v 4 He must¦56979 not make himself ‘unclean¦56979’ \add if it's the death of\add* \add ?≈a relative only by marriage\add*.
\v 5 They must¦56986 not shave¦56993 their heads or trim the edges of their beards¦56991 or cut their bodies \add in grief\add*.\x + \xo 21:5: \xt Lev 19:27-28; Deu 14:1.\x*
\p
\v 6 \add @ The priests\add* must stay separate for their God¦57001 and they must not \add ≈tarnish his reputation¦57004\add* because¦57006 they present¦57014 the gifts to Yahweh¦57010—their god's \add ≈food\add*
\v 7 They mustn't \add ?≈marry\add* a woman who was a prostitute¦57019 or who has defiled herself \add some other way\add* or who is divorced¦57024 from her¦57025 husband¦57025, because¦57028 they're separated for their god¦57032.
\v 8 You must \add ≈treat\add* him¦57034 as \add ≈set apart\add* because he's the one presenting¦57042 your god's \add ≈food\add*. He must be ‘holy’ for you, because I, Yahweh¦57050, am holy and¦57034 I set you all apart as ‘holy’.
\v 9 If a priest's¦57055 daughter¦57053 prostituted¦57058 herself¦57057, she would be profaning¦57057 her¦57061 father¦57061 \add so\add* must¦57057 be burnt¦57065 \add to death\add*.
\p
\v 10 The priest¦57068 who is chief of all his brothers¦57070 and who had the anointing¦57079 oil poured¦57073 over his head, and \add ≈who has the responsibility of\add* wearing the \add special\add* clothing, must not \add ≈wear his hair loose\add*, and he must not tear his clothes¦57087 \add in grief\add*.
\v 11 He mustn't approach \em any\em* dead¦57101 body—not \add even\add* his \add own\add* \add ≈parents\add*—he mustn't make himself¦57107 ‘unclean¦57107’.
\v 12 \add Even for a death,\add* he mustn't leave \add his duties in\add* the sanctuary, and¦57109 he mustn't profane¦57115 the sanctuary of his god, because¦57119 he's been consecrated¦57120 with the anointing¦57122 oil. I am Yahweh¦57126.
\v 13 He can \add only\add* \add ≈marry\add* a virgin¦57130—
\v 14 he mustn't take a widow¦57133 or a divorced¦57134 woman, or a defiled prostitute¦57136. He can only \add ≈marry\add* an unmarried, \add ≈Israeli\add* girl,
\v 15 then¦57150 he¦57152 won't¦57150 profane¦57152 his offspring among¦57154 his relatives, because¦57155 I¦57156 am Yahweh¦57157 who sets him¦57158 apart¦57158 as ‘holy’.
\p
\v 16 Then Yahweh¦57162 told Mosheh¦57165,
\p
\v 17 Tell Aharon that \add ≈none of his descendants\add* who have a \add ≈deformity\add* should ever approach to present¦57182 the food for his god¦57184.
\v 18 \add ≈Yes,\add* no man who has a \add ≈deformity\add* must¦57195 approach \add to offer a sacrifice\add*, i.e., no one who's blind¦57197, lame, mutilated, or \add ≈with a swelling\add*,
\v 19 or with a broken foot¦57212 or hand¦57215,
\v 20 or a hunchback¦57219 or dwarf, or with an eye¦57225 defect¦57224, with a scab or rash, or anyone with a crushed¦57231 testicle¦57232.
\v 21 Any \add ≈descendant of\add* Aharon the priest¦57243 with a blemish mustn't approach to preset a gift to Yahweh¦57250—no that person mustn't approach to present god's food.
\v 22 However, they can eat¦57267 those gifts for God¦57261, including¦57264 the sacred and¦57264 very sacred \add ≈portions\add*.
\v 23 \add ≈Despite that,\add* they mustn't enter past the curtain¦57272 or approach the altar¦57277 if they have a defect on \add ≈their¦57292 body\add*. They mustn't profane¦57285 my sanctuary¦57288 because¦57280 I am Yahweh¦57291 who sets them apart¦57292 as ‘holy’.
\p
\v 24 \add ≈So¦57294\add* Mosheh¦57295 told \add all\add* that to Aharon and his sons¦57301, and all the \add ≈Israelis¦57306\add*.
\c 22
\s1 Offerings to Yahweh become sacred
\rem /s1 The Use of Holy Offerings; The Holiness of the Offerings
\p
\v 1 Then Yahweh¦57311 told Mosheh¦57314:
\p
\v 2 Tell Aharon and his sons¦57323 that¦57335 they must¦57330 \add ≈carefully honour\add* the holy things¦57325 \add offered\add* by the \add ≈Israeli¦57326\add* people¦57326, and they mustn't profane¦57330 my holy \add ≈reputation¦57333\add*. I am Yahweh¦57340.
\v 3 Tell them that \add ≈throughout\add* the generations¦57344, any \add ≈of your descendants\add* who is ‘unclean¦57364’ and approaches things¦57357 that have become holy because the people¦57360 have consecrated them to Yahweh, \add @that person\add* will be cut off from me. I am Yahweh.
\p
\v 4 Any man who's a descendant of Aharon, if he has a skin disease¦57378 or a discharge¦57380, he mustn't eat any of the sacred \add >food\add* until¦57384 he's ‘clean’ \add again\add*. \add ≈The same applies if\add* he's touched¦57387 any ‘unclean¦57390’ corpse¦57392, anyone¦57394 who's had a seminal emission,
\v 5 anyone who's touched any swarming¦57410 \add >creature\add* that makes him ‘unclean’ or touches \add another\add* person who makes him ‘unclean’ (whatever that person's uncleanness is).
\v 6 \add No,\add* the man who's touched¦57426 any of those will be ‘unclean¦57429’ until the evening¦57432 and he mustn't eat¦57434 any of the sacred¦57437 \add >food\add* until he's washed¦57441 his body¦57442 with water¦57443.
\v 7 When¦57445 the sun¦57446 sets, then¦57445 he'll be ‘clean¦57447’ and¦57445 will be able to eat¦57449 any of those sacred¦57452 \add >offerings\add* because¦57453 that's his food.
\v 8 \add ≈But¦57458\add* he¦57460 must¦57460 \add ≈never\add* eat¦57460 \add ≈an animal found dead\add* or torn \add by wild animals\add* and¦57458 become¦57461 ‘unclean¦57461’ \add ≈in that way\add*. I¦57464 am Yahweh¦57465.
\p
\v 9 \add @The priests\add* must¦57467 \add ≈follow my instructions\add* so they won't¦57471 have to bear their¦57482 own disobedience and¦57467 die¦57476 from it because¦57478 they profaned¦57479 them. I¦57480 am Yahweh¦57481 who makes them sacred¦57482.
\p
\v 10 \add ≈However,\add* no stranger¦57486 may eat the sacred¦57490 \add >food\add*, \add e.g.,\add* someone staying with the priest¦57492, or his hired¦57493 servant.
\v 11 If the priest had purchased \add ≈the person\add* with \add ≈cash¦57505\add*, then¦57499 \add @that person\add* can eat it, plus¦57509 anyone¦57509 that was born into \add @the priest's\add* \add ≈household¦57510\add*.
\v 12 A priest's daughter¦57515 who \add ≈is married by\add* \add ≈someone who's not a priest\add* can \add no longer\add* eat¦57526 those sacred¦57524 \add ≈offerings\add*.
\v 13 \add However, in the future\add* if she became a widow¦57533 or was divorced¦57534 without having had children, and¦57528 if she has returned¦57538 to her father's house¦57541 like when she was young, then¦57528 she can eat \add ≈the same food as her father\add*, \add ≈but¦57528 no\add* stranger¦57549 may eat it.
\p
\v 14 If someone¦57556 accidentally eats something that's sacred¦57560, then they must¦57559 \add ≈pay back the full value plus¦57556 20%\add* to the priest¦57566.
\p
\v 15 \add ≈So¦57571\add* \add in summary\add*, \add @the priests\add* must¦57572 not profane¦57572 the sacred¦57575 things¦57575 \add contributed by\add* the \add ≈Israelis¦57576\add* and¦57571 which¦57579 they've \add ≈offered\add* to Yahweh¦57582
\v 16 or else they'll cause¦57584 themselves to bear the guilt¦57587 from their¦57591 disobedience concerning eating sacred \add >food\add*, because¦57592 I¦57593 am Yahweh¦57594 who has separated them to be sacred.
\rem /s1 Worthy and Unworthy Offerings; Unacceptable Sacrifices; Acceptable Offerings
\p
\v 17 The Yahweh¦57599 told Mosheh¦57602:
\p
\v 18 Tell Aharon and his sons, and all the \add ≈Israelis¦57615\add* that¦57636 any \add ≈Israeli¦57615\add* or outsider \add ≈residing\add* in Yisrael¦57616, when they present their burnt¦57640 offering to Yahweh¦57639, whether it's for a vow or for a freewill¦57635 offering,
\v 19 to be accepted¦57642 it must¦57643 be a male¦57644 with no¦57643 defects¦57643, whether it's a cow, or a sheep, or a goat.
\v 20 Anything that has a defect must¦57655 \em not\em* be presented¦57655 because¦57656 it wouldn't be acceptable¦57659 on your behalf.\x + \xo 22:20: \xt Deu 17:1.\x*
\v 21 \add ≈When¦57663 someone¦57663\add* presents¦57666 a sacrifice¦57667 of peace¦57669 offerings¦57669 to Yahweh¦57670 to fulfill¦57671 a vow or as a freewill¦57675 offering¦57675 from the herd or the flock¦57678, to be accepted¦57681 it must¦57666 \add ≈flawless with no¦57679 defects¦57679\add*—
\v 22 not blind or with broken \add bones\add*, and not maimed or with an oozing sore or rash or scab. You all mustn't present¦57705 \add ≈anything like that\add* to Yahweh, and must¦57705 not \add even\add* offering¦57708 \add ≈any part of them\add* to Yahweh on the altar¦57715.
\v 23 \add ≈However,\add* if a cow¦57718 or a sheep¦57719 has something enlarged¦57720 or something stunted¦57721, it can be offered as a freewill¦57722 offering¦57722, but¦57718 it wouldn't be accepted¦57727 for a vow,
\v 24 and¦57729 you all must¦57734 never present¦57734 to Yahweh¦57735 any animal that's bruised or torn or cut.\f + \fr 22:24 \ft The Septuagint mentions ‘testicles’ here, which also correlates with 21:20.\f* You mustn't do¦57738 that in your¦57736 \add ≈country\add*.
\p
\v 25 You all mustn't present¦57745 any of those \add animals¦57752 raised\add* by foreigners¦57743 to your god¦57749 because¦57753 they've been ruined and¦57740 are defective,\f + \fr 22:25 \ft Could this be related to the fact that they'd been neutered (as per v24 in the Septuagint)???\f* \add ≈so\add* they won't¦57744 be accepted¦57759 for you.
\p
\v 26 Then Yahweh¦57764 told Mosheh¦57767:
\p
\v 27 A \add newborn\add* calf or lamb or goat¦57776 must¦57778 \add ≈remain with\add* its mother¦57783 for seven¦57780 days¦57781—it can be offered¦57789 as a sacrifice to Yahweh¦57790 from the eighth¦57785 day¦57784 onwards¦57786,
\v 28 \add ≈but¦57792\add* you mustn't slaughter a cow¦57792 or a sheep¦57795 and¦57797 it's \add ≈offspring\add* on \add ≈the same\add* day¦57802.
\v 29 When¦57805 you \add ≈offer\add* a thanksgiving¦57810 sacrifice to Yahweh¦57811, it must¦57807 be \add ≈acceptable¦57812 as a sacrifice\add*
\v 30 and you can eat it that same day¦57815 \add but\add* \add ≈no part\add* of it should be left until¦57822 the morning¦57824. I¦57825 am Yahweh¦57826.
\p
\v 31 You all must¦57828 \add ≈record my instructions and¦57830 follow\add* them. I am Yahweh¦57833.
\v 32 You mustn't profane¦57836 the \add ≈reputation¦57839\add* of my holiness, and¦57841 I will demonstrate my holiness among the Israeli¦57843 people¦57843. I am Yahweh¦57846 who separates you all to be sacred¦57840—
\v 33 who brought¦57849 you all out of Egypt¦57852 \add (Heb. Mitsrayim)\add* to be your god¦57855. I am Yahweh¦57857.
\c 23
\s1 The scheduled festivals
\rem /s1 The Appointed Festivals; Appointed Festivals; The Religious Festivals
\p
\v 1 Then Yahweh¦57861 told Mosheh¦57864:
\p
\v 2 Tell¦57871 the \add Israelis¦57870\add* that¦57876 they¦57883 must¦57872 proclaim¦57878 Yahweh's¦57875 scheduled festivals as sacred¦57881 assemblies \add ≈at the given times\add*.
\s2 The rest day
\rem /s1 The Sabbath; The Sabbath, Passover, and Unleavened Bread
\p
\v 3 Work for six days¦57887, then the seventh¦57891 is a rest day \add for\add* a sacred¦57896 assembly¦57894—don't¦57900 work on that day—\add ≈wherever you live\add* it's a rest day \add ≈to honour\add* Yahweh¦57904.\x + \xo 23:3: \xt Exo 20:8-10; 23:12; 31:15; 34:21; 35:2; Deu 5:12-14.\x*
\rem /s1 The Passover and Unleavened Bread
\p
\v 4 \add ≈The¦57911 following\add* are the scheduled festivals that¦57914 you must¦57916 proclaim¦57916 at the appointed times as sacred¦57913 assemblies:
\s2 Passover and flat bread festivals
\rem /s1 Passover and Unleavened Bread; Passover and the Festival of Unleavened Bread
\r (Num. 28:16-25)
\v 5 The 14th of the first¦57921 month \add (Nisan = March/April) each year\add* \add ≈at twilight\add* is the \add start of the celebration to honour\add* Yahweh¦57928 with the ‘passover¦57927’.\x + \xo 23:5: \xt Exo 12:1-13; Deu 16:1-2.\x*
\p
\v 6 Then¦57930 the \add next day¦57932\add* (the 15th) is \add the start of\add* the festival¦57935 of flat bread \add to honour\add* Yahweh¦57937—you all must¦57930 eat¦57941 bread made without any rising agent for seven¦57938 days¦57939.\x + \xo 23:6-8: \xt Exo 12:14-20; 23:15; 34:18; Deu 16:3-8.\x*
\v 7 On \add &that\add* first¦57944 day you'll hold a sacred¦57947 assembly¦57945—no \add ≈regular\add* work may be done \add that day\add*.
\v 8 For seven days¦57961 you all must¦57957 present¦57957 offerings¦57958 to Yahweh¦57959, then¦57957 the seventh day is \add another\add* sacred¦57966 assembly¦57964—\add again\add* no \add ≈regular\add* work may be done \add that day\add*.
\s1 The firstfruits festival
\rem /s1 Firstfruits; The Offering of First Fruits; The Festival of Firstfruits
\p
\v 9 Then Yahweh¦57976 told Mosheh¦57979:
\p
\v 10 Tell the \add ≈Israelis¦57985\add* that when you enter the land that I'm giving you all, and you harvest \add ≈your grain crops\add*, then you all must¦57987 bring¦58003 a sheaf¦58006 of the first¦58007 \add part\add* of your harvest to a priest¦58011,
\v 11 and¦58013 he will wave the sheaf¦58016 \add ≈in front¦58017\add* of Yahweh¦58018 \add ≈to be accepted¦58019 for you\add*. That must¦58013 be done the day after the rest day.
\v 12 \add ≈That same\add* day¦58026, you¦58027 all must¦58025 offer a year-old lamb¦58031 \add ≈with no¦58032 defects¦58032\add* to Yahweh¦58037 as a burnt¦58036 offering¦58036,
\v 13 and the \add associated\add* grain¦58039 offering will be two kilograms of fine wheat flour¦58042 mixed¦58043 with \add olive\add* oil. That will be a gift to Yahweh¦58046 with a pleasing¦58048 aroma¦58047, and the \add associated\add* drink¦58049 offering will be a litre of wine.
\v 14 You all may not eat¦58059 any bread¦58055, or roasted¦58056 or fresh grain¦58056, on that day¦58063, until \add after\add* you've taken the offering to your god¦58070. That is a \add ≈rule that will continue throughout\add* your generations¦58073 \add ≈no matter where\add* you live.
\s1 The fiftieth day festival
\rem /s1 Feast of Weeks; The Festival of Weeks; The Festival of Harvest; The Harvest Festival
\r (Num. 28:26-31)
\p
\v 15 Then count¦58078 seven rest days from the day after you brought¦58083 the \add ≈bundle of grain\add* as a wave offering—seven full weeks.\x + \xo 23:15-21: \xt Exo 23:16; 34:22; Deu 16:9-12.\x*
\v 16 Then that next day¦58094 \add will make\add* fifty¦58098 days, and¦58100 then you all must¦58097 present¦58100 a new grain¦58101 offering¦58101 to Yahweh¦58103.
\v 17 From your \add ≈homes\add*, \add @each family\add* must¦58106 bring¦58106 two loaves of bread¦58108 baked¦58116 with a rising agent, as a firstfruits¦58117 \add offering\add* to Yahweh¦58118.
\v 18 Along with the bread¦58123, you all must¦58120 present¦58120 seven¦58124 \add ≈year-old\add* male lambs¦58125 \add ≈without¦58126 defects¦58126\add*, one \add ≈young¦58130\add* bull¦58129, and two rams. They will be a burnt¦58137 offering to Yahweh, with their \add associated\add* grain¦58139 and drink¦58140 offerings¦58140—a gift with a pleasing¦58144 aroma¦58142 for Yahweh.
\v 19 You all must¦58147 \add also\add* offer a male goat¦58148 as a sin offering and¦58147 two \add ≈one-year-old\add* male lambs¦58154 as a peace¦58158 offering.
\v 20 The priest must¦58160 raise them along with the firstfruits¦58166 bread¦58165 as a wave offering \add ≈in front¦58168\add* of Yahweh, with the two lambs¦58173. They will become sacred¦58174 to Yahweh, \add but¦58160\add* for the priest \add to eat\add*.
\v 21 You all must¦58179 proclaim¦58179 a sacred¦58186 assembly¦58184 that same day¦58182—you mustn't do¦58194 any \add ≈regular¦58195\add* work¦58191. That is a \add ≈permanent¦58196\add* rule that will continue \add ≈throughout\add* the generations¦58200 \add ≈no matter where you live\add*.
\p
\v 22 When¦58202 you all harvest your \add ≈crops\add*, don't \add ≈reap\add* to the very edge of your field¦58211 and don't \add ≈pick up stalks that drop on the ground\add*—they must¦58209 be left for the poor and for foreigners \add without land\add*. I¦58221 am your god¦58223, Yahweh¦58222.\x + \xo 23:22: \xt Lev 19:9-10; Deu 24:19-22.\x*
\s1 The new year festival
\rem /s1 The Festival of Trumpets; Feast of Trumpets; The New Year Festival
\r (Num. 29:1-6)
\p
\v 23 Then Yahweh¦58227 told Mosheh¦58230,
\v 24 “Tell the \add ≈Israelis¦58236\add* that on the 1st of the seventh¦58240 month \add (Tishrei = September/October) each year\add*, you must¦58243 have a \add ≈public holiday\add* with a loud¦58247 \add trumpet\add* blast¦58247 announcing the sacred¦58250 assembly¦58248.
\v 25 You all must not do¦58257 any \add ≈regular\add* work¦58254 on that day, and¦58258 you all must present¦58258 a fire-offering to Yahweh¦58260.”
\s1 The day of atonement
\rem /s1 The Day of Atonement
\r (Num. 29:7-11)
\p
\v 26 Then Yahweh¦58264 told Mosheh¦58267,\x + \xo 23:26-32: \xt Lev 16:29-34.\x*
\v 27 “The 10th of that seventh¦58273 month¦58272 is a day¦58275 \add ≈for making things right\add* \add with Yahweh\add*. You all \add ≈must¦58281 hold a sacred¦58280 assembly¦58278\add* and humble \add ≈yourselves\add* and present¦58287 a fire-offering to Yahweh.
\v 28 You mustn't do any work on that particular day because¦58299 it's the day for \add ≈making yourselves¦58304 right\add* in front¦58305 of your god Yahweh¦58306,
\v 29 because anyone who doesn't humble¦58316 themself on that day¦58318 will be cut off from their people.
\v 30 ⇔\add In addition¦58323,\add* I¦58334 will destroy¦58334 anyone who works on that day¦58332—removing them from their people¦58340.
\v 31 You all must¦58346 not do¦58346 any work¦58344. That's a permanent¦58348 rule that will continue \add ≈throughout\add* the generations¦58349 \add ≈no matter where you live\add*—
\v 32 it's a \add ≈very strict\add* rest day¦58361 and¦58357 you all must¦58357 humble yourselves from the evening of the 9th until¦58365 the next evening when \add *it\add* will finish.
\s1 The celebration in shelters
\rem /s1 The Festival of Shelters; The Festival of Booths; Feast of Tabernacles
\r (Num. 29:12-40)
\p
\v 33 Then Yahweh¦58373 told Mosheh¦58376:\x + \xo 23:33-36: \xt Deu 16:13-15.\x*
\p
\v 34 Tell the \add ≈Israelis¦58382\add* that \add starting\add* on the 15th of the seventh¦58389 month¦58388 \add (of Tishrei—around September/October)\add*, there will be a celebration in shelters to \add honour\add* Yahweh¦58395.
\v 35 The first¦58398 day¦58397 will be a sacred¦58401 assembly¦58399—you all mustn't do¦58407 any \add ≈regular\add* work¦58404.
\v 36 You all must¦58411 present a gift to Yahweh \add each day\add* for seven days¦58410, and then on the eighth¦58415 day, there'll be \add another\add* sacred¦58418 assembly¦58424 and you'll all present a gift to Yahweh. It'll be \add a day\add* to assemble—you all mustn't do any \add ≈regular\add* work \add that day\add*.
\p
\v 37 \add @The above\add* are the \add ≈scheduled dates\add* to proclaim¦58438 sacred¦58441 assemblies to present¦58442 a gift to Yahweh¦58435: burnt¦58445 offerings and grain¦58446 offerings, sacrifices¦58447 and drink¦58448 offerings, on the \add ≈appropriate\add* days,
\v 38 as well as Yahweh's¦58456 rest days, and alongside all your \add regular\add* gifts¦58458 and vows and freewill¦58466 offerings¦58466 that¦58467 you all give¦58468 to Yahweh.
\p
\v 39 \add ≈So indeed,\add* on the 15th of the seventh month¦58475 when you have \add ≈harvested your crops\add*, you'll all celebrate¦58482 Yahweh's¦58487 festival for seven days with the first¦58491 and eighth¦58494 days being rest days.
\v 40 On that first¦58500 day, you'll all bring the fruit¦58501 from your trees¦58505, along with palm branches, leafy¦58509 branches, and willow branches from \add beside\add* the \add #creeks\add*, and you'll all \add ≈happily celebrate\add* \add ≈in front¦58514\add* of your god Yahweh¦58515 for seven¦58517 days.
\v 41 Do that for seven¦58524 days¦58525 each year¦58526 as a festival to \add honour\add* Yahweh¦58523. you all must¦58520 celebrate it in the seventh month¦58530. That's a permanent¦58528 rule that will continue \add ≈throughout\add* the generations¦58529.
\v 42 You all must¦58536 live in shelters for seven¦58537 days¦58538—all you native-born \add ≈Israelis\add*,
\v 43 so that the \add future\add* generations¦58548 will know¦58547 that I made \add ≈their ancestors\add* live in shelters when I brought¦58556 them out of Egypt¦58559 \add (Heb. Mitsrayim)\add*. I am your god¦58562 Yahweh¦58561.
\p
\v 44 \add ≈So¦58564\add* Mosheh¦58565 \add ≈passed\add* all those \add ≈scheduled dates\add* from Yahweh¦58569, on to the \add ≈Israelis¦58572\add*.
\c 24
\s1 Oil for the lamps
\rem /s1 Taking Care of the Lamps; Pure Oil and Holy Bread; The Lamp; Oil and Bread Set Before the Lord
\r (Exo. 27:20-21)
\p
\v 1 Then Yahweh¦58577 told Mosheh¦58580:
\p
\v 2 Order¦58587 the \add ≈Israelis¦58586\add* to bring¦58588 you¦58589 pressed¦58593 olive¦58591 oil¦58590 that's pure, to \add ≈supply\add* \add #lamps\add* \add to give\add* continual¦58597 light¦58594.
\v 3 \add The high priest\add* (Aharon) \add ≈must¦58604 take care of\add* \add #them\add* from evening¦58607 until¦58608 the morning¦58610 \add to burn\add* continually \add ≈in front¦58611\add* of Yahweh¦58612. That's a permanent¦58615 requirement that will continue \add ≈throughout\add* the generations¦58616.
\v 4 He will arrange¦58621 the lamps continually¦58627 on the lampstand \add ≈in front¦58625\add* of Yahweh¦58626.
\s1 The bread offered there to God
\rem /s1 The Bread for the Tabernacle; The Bread Offered to God
\p
\v 5 \add Each week\add* you must¦58630 take¦58630 fine wheat flour and bake twelve loaves of bread, using two kilograms of flour for each loaf.\x + \xo 24:5-6: \xt Exo 25:30.\x*
\v 6 \add ≈Arrange\add* the loaves into two¦58645 rows of six¦58647 loaves on the pure table¦58650 \add ≈in front¦58652\add* of Yahweh¦58653,
\v 7 and¦58661 put pure frankincense¦58659 \add ≈with\add* each row to be a memorial¦58663 portion for the bread¦58662 as a gift to Yahweh¦58665.
\v 8 \add Every¦58678\add* rest day \add ≈it will be placed\add* \add ≈in front¦58672\add* of Yahweh¦58673 \add representing\add* the \add ≈ongoing\add* agreement¦58679 with the \add ≈Israelis¦58676\add*.
\v 9 \add ≈Afterwards,\add* it will belong¦58682 to Aharon and his sons¦58684, and they must¦58682 eat¦58685 it in a sacred area because¦58688 it's a \add ≈very\add* sacred part of the gifts for Yahweh¦58694. That's a permanent¦58697 rule.\x + \xo 24:9: \xt Mat 12:4; Mrk 2:26; Luk 6:4.\x*
\s1 Execution for cursing Yahweh
\rem /s1 An Example of Just and Fair Punishment; An Example of Just Punishment; A Blasphemer Stoned; Blasphemy and Its Punishment
\p
\v 10 \add ≈Once\add* there was an Israeli woman¦58703 and an Egyptian man \add ≈who had\add* a son who \add ≈lived among the Israelis¦58711\add*, and he \add ≈got into a fight\add* with an Israeli man.
\v 11 Then¦58720 that son of the Israeli¦58724 woman¦58723 slandered¦58720 \add &Yahweh's\add* name and cursed¦58728, and \add so\add* the people¦58729 took him to Mosheh¦58733. (The mother¦58735 was Shelomit¦58736, a daughter¦58737 of Dibri¦58739 from the Dan¦58742 tribe¦58740.)
\v 12 They \add ≈held\add* him¦58744 in custody¦58745 \add ≈while waiting for Yahweh's¦58751 decision\add*.
\p
\v 13 Then Yahweh¦58755 told Mosheh¦58758:
\p
\v 14 Take \add ≈that man\add* who cursed¦58764 outside¦58767 the camp¦58768, and \add ≈everyone¦58764 who heard¦58772 him\add* must place their¦58775 hands¦58775 on his head¦58778, and then \add ≈all the people must execute him by throwing rocks¦58779 at\add* him.
\v 15 Then¦58785 tell the \add ≈people¦58787\add* that anyone who curses¦58795 God¦58796 must¦58789 bear \add the results of\add* their own wickedness.
\v 16 Anyone¦58800 who slanders Yahweh's¦58803 \add ≈reputation¦58801\add* must be executed. The \add gathered assembly\add* must \add ≈throw rocks¦58806 at\add* them. \add It makes no difference\add* whether they're a \add ≈foreigner staying there\add*, or a native-born \add Israeli\add*.
\p
\v 17 Anyone who \add ≈murders\add* another person, must¦58822 \add ≈definitely be executed\add*.\x + \xo 24:17: \xt Exo 21:12.\x*
\v 18 Anyone¦58830 who kills \add someone else's\add* animal, must¦58834 \add ≈make restitution with the same kind of animal\add*.
\p
\v 19 Anyone who \add ≈injures\add* a fellow¦58844 citizen¦58844, must¦58842 have the same done to them—
\v 20 fracture for fracture, eye for eye, tooth for tooth—\add ≈however they injured the other person¦58863, that's what must¦58861 be done to them\add*.\x + \xo 24:20: \xt Exo 21:23-25; Deu 19:21; Mat 5:38.\x*
\v 21 Anyone¦58868 who kills \add someone else's\add* animal¦58869 must \add ≈replace\add* it¦58870, \add ≈but¦58868\add* anyone¦58868 who kills \add another\add* person¦58872 must be executed.
\v 22 There's \add only\add* one \add set of\add* regulations for \add both\add* the foreigner and the native-born \add citizen\add* because¦58882 I am your god¦58885 Yahweh¦58884.\x + \xo 24:22: \xt Num 15:16.\x*
\p
\v 23 Mosheh \add ≈passed\add* \add all that\add* onto the \add ≈people¦58891\add*, and¦58887 they took the \add ≈man who had cursed¦58896\add* \add Yahweh\add* outside¦58899 the camp¦58900 \add ≈where\add* they \add ≈executed him with rocks\add*. The Israelis¦58891 did¦58907 exactly what Yahweh had commanded¦58909 \add them\add* via Mosheh.
\c 25
\s1 The rest year
\rem /s1 The Sabbatical Year; The Seventh Year; The Sabbath Year
\r (Deu. 15:1-11)
\p
\v 1 Then on Mt¦58921. Sinai¦58922, Yahweh¦58917 told Mosheh¦58920:\x + \xo 25:1-7: \xt Exo 23:10-11.\x*
\p
\v 2 Tell the \add ≈Israelis¦58928\add* that when you all enter the land that I'm giving you, the land must¦58930 \add observe\add* a \add ≈rest year\add* for Yahweh¦58944.
\v 3 ⇔You can \add ≈plant your crops\add*, prune¦58952 your \add ≈grapevines\add*, and \add ≈harvest\add* \add all\add* its produce¦58957 for six years,
\v 4 but¦58959 during the seventh¦58960 year¦58959, you must¦58963 \add ≈allow the land to rest\add* \add to honour\add* Yahweh¦58966. You mustn't \add ≈plant any crops or prune¦58972 any grapevines\add*.
\v 5 Don't¦58977 \add systematically\add* harvest the self-sown \add ≈crops\add* or the grapes from the untrimmed¦58982 vines. It must¦58978 be a rest year for the land.
\v 6 \add ≈However, during\add* the rest year, the land \add ≈will provide\add* food for you and your servants, and for your hired¦58998 workers and the foreigners who are living among you,
\v 7 as well as your livestock¦59003 and¦59003 the \add wild\add* animals¦59004 across the land. Any produce¦59010 from the land can be eaten.
\s1 The restoration celebration year
\rem /s1 The Year of Jubilee; The Year of Restoration
\p
\v 8 Count off seven rest years, so seven times¦59022 seven which is forty-nine years,
\v 9 then¦59033 \add after that\add*, sound¦59035 loud¦59035 horn blasts¦59035 on the 10th of the seventh¦59037 month \add ≈to announce\add* throughout¦59033 the land that it's the day¦59040 for \add ≈making things right with Yahweh\add*.
\v 10 Then¦59048 you all must¦59048 \add ≈declare\add* \add &that\add* fiftieth year \add ≈to be sacred¦59048\add*. It'll be a \add ≈restoration celebration\add* \add year\add* when you announce freedom for all the inhabitants¦59058 of the \add ≈country\add*—everyone¦59064 can be free to return to their families, and¦59048 \add all families can be free\add* to return to their \add ≈originally inherited land\add*.
\v 11 That fiftieth year will be a \add ≈restoration celebration\add* year. You all mustn't \add ≈plant crops\add* and don't¦59081 \add systematically\add* harvest¦59084 the self-sown \add ≈crops\add* or the grapes¦59089 from the untrimmed¦59092 vines¦59092,
\v 12 because it's a \add ≈restoration celebration\add* year. You all must¦59098 \add treat it\add* as sacred¦59097 and \add just\add* eat¦59103 \add ≈what you take\add* \add directly\add* from the countryside¦59102.
\p
\v 13 In that \add ≈restoration celebration\add* year¦59108, you all should return¦59111 to your \add ≈inherited land\add*.
\v 14 \add In the other years\add* when you buy or sell¦59120 from your fellow citizens, you mustn't \add ≈cheat\add* them
\v 15 \add because the value of the land\add* \add ≈will depend\add* on the number of years after¦59136 the \add ≈restoration celebration\add* year, \add i.e., \add* you must¦59138 take into account the number of years of produce¦59144—
\v 16 if there's many years \add to go\add*, the price will increase¦59153, and \add ≈if the next rest year is close\add*, the price will decrease because¦59160 you're selling¦59164 the number¦59161 of crops.
\v 17 \add ≈So¦59167\add* don't¦59167 cheat eat other—you must¦59168 \add ≈respect and¦59167 obey\add* your god, because¦59175 I¦59176 am your god Yahweh¦59177.
\rem /s1 The Problem of the Seventh Year
\p
\v 18 You all must¦59180 \add ≈follow\add* all my instructions¦59183 and¦59180 \add ≈maintain\add* my \add ≈values\add*—keeping them \add ≈so that\add* you'll be able to live securely¦59194 on the land.
\v 19 The land will \add ≈yield its¦59198 crops\add* and you'll all \add ≈have plenty to eat¦59199\add*, and you'll be able to live \add *there\add* securely¦59202.
\p
\v 20 \add ≈But¦59205\add* if you all \add ≈wonder\add* what you'll eat¦59209 in \add &that\add* seventh¦59213 year¦59212 when you'll neither \add ≈plant crops\add* or \add ≈do organised harvests\add*,
\v 21 \add ≈well\add* I'll¦59223 \add ≈send\add* my blessing¦59226 to you all in the sixth¦59229 year¦59228, and¦59223 it'll produce¦59233 enough for three¦59234 years¦59235
\v 22 \add ≈so\add* you all can still eat that \add ≈stored\add* food while you \add ≈plant crops\add* in the eighth¦59240 year \add ≈to feed you all through\add* the ninth¦59249 year.
\s1 Returning property to the clan
\rem /s1 Restoration of Property
\p
\v 23 The land can not be \add ≈irrevocably\add* sold, because¦59261 it¦59259 belongs to me and you all are foreigners and temporary residents¦59268 \add ≈on my\add* \add land\add*.
\rem /s1 Redemption of Property
\v 24 \add ≈so\add* for all the land \add ≈that you take possession¦59274 of\add*, \add ≈there must¦59276 be a way to get back the family\add* land.
\v 25 \add For example,\add* if an \add ≈Israeli man\add* becomes¦59282 poor and sells off some of his \add ≈inherited land\add*, then a close relative \add must¦59282 have the right to\add* go and \add ≈buy back\add* that land.
\v 26 Even if he didn't¦59297 have \add ≈a relative who could do that\add*, and he prospers again \add in the future\add* and is \add ≈able to raise enough money\add*,
\v 27 then he can calculate¦59308 \add ≈the value of the years¦59311\add* \add until the restoration celebration\add*, and¦59308 then \add ≈for that amount\add* he \add ≈must¦59308 be allowed to\add* \add ≈buy the land back from the person¦59317 he'd sold it to\add*.
\v 28 \add ≈However,\add* if \add ≈the original owner wasn't able to raise enough money\add*, then¦59325 that \add ≈piece of land that\add* was sold will remain \add ≈under the control of the buyer\add* until¦59338 the \add ≈restoration celebration\add* year¦59339 when it must¦59341 be returned¦59343 \add anyway\add*.
\p
\v 29 If a house¦59350 inside a walled city¦59353 is sold, then¦59346 the right \add ≈to buy it back\add* will last until¦59357 one full year¦59360 after the sale.
\v 30 If it's not bought¦59387 back \add by the original family\add* within that year, then that house¦59377 in the walled city¦59380 will then belong permanently to the buyer—it won't¦59367 \add ≈be returned in the restoration celebration year\add*.
\v 31 \add ≈On the contrary,\add* village¦59395 houses¦59394 will be considered as part of the family land, so they'll be able to be bought back \add by the family\add*, \add ≈otherwise they'll be returned in the restoration celebration year\add*.
\p
\v 32 The Levites' cities and¦59414 houses¦59416 will belong¦59421 to them permanently—the Levites \add ≈must¦59421 \+em always¦59420\+em* be able to buy them back\add*,
\v 33 \add ≈but¦59424\add* \add even\add* if \add *they\add* \add ?don't\add* \add ≈buy them back\add*, they must¦59425 be \add ≈returned in the restoration celebration year\add* because¦59436 the Levites' houses¦59437 are their¦59441 \add only\add* possession among the \add ≈Israelis¦59443\add*.
\v 34 \add ≈In addition¦59446,\add* they may not sell¦59450 the pastureland¦59447 around their cities¦59448 because¦59451 that's their permanent¦59454 possession¦59453.
\s1 Assisting the poor
\rem /s1 Loans to the Poor; Redemption of the Poor and Enslaved
\p
\v 35 If \add ≈a fellow citizen\add* becomes¦59461 poor and \add ≈is unable to survive\add* beside you, then you must¦59461 \add ≈support\add* \add @that person\add* and \add ≈allow him to live¦59470 with you like a foreigner might\add*.\x + \xo 25:35: \xt Deu 15:7-8.\x*
\v 36 You mustn't \add ≈charge\add* \add @that person\add* any interest¦59477 \add ≈or make a profit from him¦59476\add*, \add ≈but¦59478\add* you must¦59479 \add ≈respect and obey\add* your god¦59480, and your \add ≈fellow citizen\add* can \add continue\add* to live¦59481 with you.
\v 37 \add ≈If you loan him money\add*, don't¦59488 \add ≈charge\add* interest¦59492 \add ≈or make a profit from his\add* food.\x + \xo 25:37: \xt Exo 22:25; Deu 23:19-20.\x*
\v 38 I am your god Yahweh¦59500 who brought¦59504 you all out of Egypt¦59507 \add (Heb. Mitsrayim)\add* to give you the Kanaan \add ≈region¦59506\add* \add and\add* to be your god.
\s1 Treatment of slaves
\rem /s1 Release of Slaves
\p
\v 39 If \add ≈a fellow citizen\add* becomes¦59521 poor and selling himself¦59524 to you, don't¦59527 \add ≈force him to work like a slave¦59532\add*—\x + \xo 25:39-46: \xt Exo 21:2-6; Deu 15:12-18.\x*
\v 40 \add ≈treat him\add* like a hired¦59534 worker or a temporary resident¦59535. He can work with you until¦59538 the \add ≈restoration celebration\add* year¦59540
\v 41 \add ≈when he must¦59545 be released\add* \add ≈along with\add* his children, and he can return to his family, and to \add ≈his clan's land\add*,
\v 42 because they are my slaves that I¦59566 brought¦59566 out of Egypt¦59569 so they mustn't be sold \add again\add* as slaves.
\v 43 Don't rule harshly¦59579 over \add #them\add* \add ≈but¦59580 rather\add*, \add ≈respect and¦59580 obey\add* your¦59581 god¦59581.
\v 44 \add ≈If you want to have\add* male or female slaves, they you can buy them from the surrounding countries¦59590,
\v 45 or else from the children or clans of the foreigners who are living among you—you all can \add ≈own¦59613 them\add*
\v 46 and¦59615 then¦59615 pass them on to your children to own¦59621 as their inheritance¦59615. You¦59628 all can make them work indefinitely \add for you\add*, but¦59615 you mustn't harshly¦59635 oppress your \add ≈fellow Israelis¦59626\add*.
\p
\v 47 If a foreigner living among you \add ≈becomes wealthy\add*, \add ≈yet\add* your \add ≈fellow citizen\add* becomes poor and sells himself¦59647 to that resident foreigner or to a member¦59652 of their clan,
\v 48 then there's always the right¦59658 of redemption¦59658 even after he's sold himself¦59657, \add so\add* one of his brothers¦59663 can \add ≈buy him¦59664 back\add*,
\v 49 or his uncle or \add ≈cousin\add* or another relative¦59676 from the clan can \add ≈pay to free him\add*. \add ≈In fact,\add* he might even be able to \add ≈buy his own way out\add*.
\v 50 He must¦59686 \add ≈work out\add* with his master how many years from when he sold himself¦59691, until¦59693 the \add ≈restoration celebration\add* year, and¦59686 \add ≈figure out\add* the price according¦59701 to the wages of a hired¦59702 worker for that many years.
\v 51 If there's still¦59708 a lot of years¦59710 \add ≈to go\add*, he'd need to repay¦59712 \add ≈most\add* of \add ≈what he sold himself for\add*,
\v 52 \add ≈but¦59717\add* if it's only a few years \add ≈to go\add*, \add ≈the price for his freedom would be proportionally smaller\add*.
\v 53 While he works for \add @the foreign master\add*, he must be treated like an annual hired¦59736 worker. \add ≈You others must ensure that he's not treated\add* harshly¦59744.
\v 54 Then¦59747 even if he's not \add ≈bought¦59750 out\add*, he and¦59747 his children must¦59750 be released in the \add ≈restoration celebration\add* year¦59753
\v 55 because the \add ≈Israelis¦59762\add* are my slaves—my slaves because I brought¦59770 them out of Egypt¦59773. I am your god¦59776 Yahweh¦59775.
\c 26
\s1 Obedience will lead to prosperity
\rem /s1 Rewards for Obedience; Reward for Obedience; Blessings for Obedience
\r (Deu. 7:12-24; 28:1-14)
\p
\v 1 You all mustn't make worthless¦59782 idols¦59782 or carved¦59790 images for yourselves, or set up sacred¦59784 pillars¦59784. In your country, you must never bow down to an \add engraved\add* stone¦59789 image, because¦59796 I am your god¦59799 Yahweh¦59798.\x + \xo 26:1: a \xt Lev 19:4; \xo b \xt Exo 20:4; Deu 5:8; 16:21-22; 27:1.\x*
\v 2 You all must¦59804 \add ≈observe\add* my rest days and¦59805 \add ≈honour\add* my sanctuary¦59805. I am Yahweh¦59808.
\p
\v 3 If you'll all \add ≈follow my instructions¦59813\add* and \add ≈remember my rules and obey\add* them,
\v 4 then¦59822 I'll¦59822 give you all rain \add ≈in the proper season\add*, and the land will produce crops and the trees in the countryside¦59829 will produce fruit¦59831.
\v 5 The \add grain\add* threshing¦59835 will \add ≈continue until\add* the grape harvest, and the grape harvesting will \add ≈continue until\add* \add ≈it's time to plant new crops\add*, and so you'll all have \add ≈plenty of food¦59845\add* and you'll live securely¦59848 \add there\add* on your land.
\p
\v 6 Then¦59851 I'll give¦59851 peace¦59852 \add ≈in your country\add* \add ≈so that\add* you'll all sleep \add ≈without being afraid\add*. I'll \add ≈remove\add* the wild animals¦59858 from your \add ≈area\add* and¦59851 there'll¦59855 be no \add ≈raids or wars\add* in your \add ≈region¦59867\add*.
\v 7 You'll all \add be able to\add* chase away your enemies¦59872 and¦59873 \add ≈destroy them\add*—
\v 8 five¦59880 of you will chase away a hundred, and a hundred of you will chase away ten¦59884 thousand¦59884, and you'll \add ≈be able to defeat\add* your enemies¦59887.
\p
\v 9 I'll \add ≈give you all my attention\add* and \add ≈bless¦59893 you with many¦59895 children\add*, and I'll \add ≈maintain\add* my agreement¦59900 with you all.
\v 10 You'll all \add still\add* \add ≈be eating the previous year's grain\add* when the new harvest \add ≈starts\add*, and¦59903 you'll have to \add ≈move\add* out \add ≈that left-over grain\add* \add to make room for the new\add*.
\v 11 Then¦59911 I'll¦59911 put my residence among¦59913 you all and¦59914 won't¦59914 \add ≈reject\add* you,
\v 12 and I'll¦59920 walk¦59920 among¦59921 you and be your god¦59924, and you'll all be my people¦59929.
\v 13 I am your¦59944 god¦59933 Yahweh¦59932 who brought¦59935 you all out from being¦59939 slaves¦59941 in Egypt¦59938, and I broke¦59942 the \add ≈chains off you\add* \add ≈so that you all could walk¦59945 with heads erect\add*.
\s1 Punishments for disobedience
\rem /s1 Punishment for Disobedience; Penalties for Disobedience; Punishments for Disobedience
\r (Deu. 28:15-68)
\p
\v 14 \add ≈However,\add* if you all won't listen¦59953 to me and won't \add ≈follow all those instructions\add*,\x + \xo 26:14-33: \xt Deu 28:15-68.\x*
\v 15 and if you¦59980 all reject¦59966 my regulations¦59965 and my \add ≈values\add* \add ≈to the point of\add* hating my commands¦59979, thus breaking¦59980 my agreement¦59983,
\v 16 then this is what I'll do¦59988 to you all: I'll \add ≈send\add* sudden¦59994 terror¦59994 to you all, and \add ≈wasting diseases and sicknesses\add*. You'll all \add ≈be wasting your time\add* sowing seeds \add ≈because\add* your enemies¦60009 will eat¦60008 \add @the harvest\add*.
\v 17 I'll¦60011 \add ≈take action\add* against you, and you'll be defeated¦60014 by your enemies¦60016. You'll be ruled over by those¦60019 who hate¦60019 you, and you'll all \add ≈run away frightened\add* \add even\add* when no one's chasing you.
\p
\v 18 If you all \add still\add* won't¦60032 listen¦60033 to me \add ≈after that\add*, then I'll¦60035 continue on to discipline¦60036 you seven¦60038 times over for your \add ≈disobedience\add*.
\v 19 Then¦60043 I'll \add ≈smash\add* your strong pride¦60046, and I'll make the sky like iron \add with no rain\add* and your land \add hard\add* like bronze¦60056.
\v 20 Your \add ≈energy spent working\add* your land will be \add just\add* wasted \add ≈as\add* your land won't \add ≈produce its crops\add*, and¦60058 the trees won't \add ≈produce any fruit¦60072\add*.
\p
\v 21 Then¦60074 if you're all \add still\add* \add ≈being contrary¦60078\add* and¦60074 unwilling to listen¦60081 to me, then¦60074 I'll¦60083 \add ≈send\add* seven¦60086 times more plagues¦60085 according¦60087 to your \add ≈disobedience\add*.
\v 22 Then¦60089 I'll¦60089 send¦60089 in the wild animals¦60093 \add ≈to\add* make you childless¦60095 and to cut back your livestocks¦60100, \add ≈thus diminishing¦60101 your numbers\add* and \add leaving\add* your roads¦60104 desolate¦60103.
\p
\v 23 Then¦60106 \add ≈after that\add* if you¦60110 all \add still\add* \add ≈won't¦60109 accept my discipline¦60110\add* and¦60112 \add ≈continue to oppose\add* me,
\v 24 then¦60116 I myself will \add ≈oppose\add* you all and¦60122 \add ≈punish\add* you all seven¦60127 times over for your \add ≈disobedience\add*.
\v 25 I'll \add ≈send armies against\add* you all to avenge¦60135 \add ≈the breaking of our agreement¦60138\add*. You'll be \add ≈shut into\add* your cities¦60142 \add ≈where\add* I'll send diseases in for you all, and¦60132 \add ≈allow your enemies to defeat\add* you.
\v 26 When I \add ≈limit your food¦60155 supplies\add*, ten women¦60158 will bake bread in one oven and \add ≈it will be rationed\add* by weight¦60164—you'll all eat \add ≈but¦60156 never\add* be satisfied¦60167.
\p
\v 27 In spite of \add all\add* that, if you all \add still\add* won't¦60173 listen¦60174 to me, and \add ≈continue to oppose\add* me,
\v 28 then¦60180 I'll \add ≈be in a hostile rage against\add* you all and¦60185 I'll discipline¦60185 you seven¦60190 times \add more\add* for your \add ≈disobedience\add*
\v 29 and you'll \add start\add* eating your own sons¦60198 and daughters¦60200.
\v 30 I'll destroy¦60203 your \add ≈hilltop shrines\add* and cut down you incense¦60210 altars¦60210, then¦60203 I'll \add ≈pile\add* your corpses on top of your idols' corpses, and I myself will detest you all.
\v 31 I'll make your cities¦60226 into \add ≈heaps of rubble\add* and I'll devastate¦60228 your sanctuaries¦60231 and \add no longer\add* smell¦60233 the pleasing¦60235 aromas \add of your sacrifices\add*.
\p
\v 32 I'll¦60237 devastate¦60237 the \add ≈region\add*, and¦60237 your enemies¦60244 who live in it¦60246 will be appalled¦60242.
\v 33 Then¦60248 I'll¦60249 scatter¦60249 you all among¦60250 \add other\add* nations¦60250 and then¦60248 \add ≈armies will come in\add* after¦60252 you and your land will become desolate¦60256 and your cities¦60257 will become \add ≈rubble\add*,
\v 34 and the land will enjoy all its rest \add ≈times\add* while it's desolate¦60269 and you're all in your enemies' \add ≈countries\add*. The land will \add ≈stop producing\add* and \add ≈enjoy its times of resting\add*.
\v 35 It will rest all through its desolation¦60284 since it didn't¦60288 get its rest times when you lived on it.
\p
\v 36 Then¦60295 those¦60295 of you who are left in your enemies' countries, I'll¦60297 make \add ≈you paranoid\add* \add there¦60312\add*—even the sound¦60304 of a blowing leaf will make them run away as if someone's chasing them with a sword¦60310, and¦60295 they'll fall down even when no one's chasing them.
\v 37 They'll stumble¦60315 over each other as if \add ≈being attacked\add*, but¦60315 there¦60323 won't be anyone¦60322 chasing them, and¦60315 then¦60315 you all won't have the energy to stand¦60328 up against your enemies¦60330.
\v 38 You'll die in \add various\add* countries¦60333 and¦60332 your enemies¦60337 will consume¦60334 you.
\v 39 Those of you who are left will rot away amongst¦60340 the wickedness in your enemies' countries and¦60339 because of the wickedness of their ancestors¦60347.
\p
\v 40 \add ≈However,\add* if they confess¦60351 their wickedness and their ancestors' wickedness, that¦60360 they've disobeyed and neglected me, and \add ≈been hostile towards\add* me,
\v 41 (and that I became hostile toward them and took their into their enemies' countries,) and humble¦60384 their \add ≈undisciplined\add* hearts¦60385 and \add ≈admit their disobedience\add*,
\v 42 then¦60393 I'll remember my agreements with Yakov \add (Jacob)\add* and with Yitshak \add (Isaac¦60402)\add* and with Avraham, and I'll remember \add &this\add* land.
\v 43 The land \add here\add* will have been deserted¦60419 by them and will have enjoyed its \add ≈times of rest\add*, and they'll accept their wickedness because¦60426 they rejected¦60429 my \add ≈values\add* and they \add ≈really\add* detested my regulations¦60432.
\v 44 \add ≈Despite that\add*, I won't reject¦60446 them in their enemies' countries, and I won't detest them enough to completely destroy them \add and\add* to break¦60451 my agreement¦60452 with them, because¦60454 I am their god¦60457 Yahweh¦60456.
\v 45 I'll¦60459 remember¦60459 the \add ≈earlier\add* agreement¦60461 with their ancestors that I brought¦60464 out of Egypt¦60468 while all the nations¦60470 watched me be their god¦60473. I am Yahweh¦60475.
\p
\v 46 \add ≈The above\add* are the \add ≈instructions¦60478 and values and rules\add* that¦60481 Yahweh¦60483 \add ≈instilled\add* between him and the \add ≈Israelis¦60486\add* through Mosheh¦60492 \add (Moses)\add* there at Mt¦60488. Sinai¦60489.
\c 27
\s1 Valuations of vows to Yahweh
\rem /s1 Votive Offerings; Redeeming Gifts Offered to the Lord; Laws concerning Gifts to the Lord; Redeeming What Is the Lord's
\p
\v 1 Then Yahweh¦60496 told Mosheh¦60499:
\p
\v 2 Tell¦60506 the \add ≈Israelis¦60505\add* that when someone makes a special vow \add ≈to offer someone\add* to Yahweh¦60515,
\v 3 a man between twenty¦60521 and¦60517 sixty¦60526 will be valued at fifty¦60530 silver¦60532 \add ≈coins\add* (according to the sanctuary standard weights)
\v 4 and¦60540 a woman at thirty¦60542 coins.
\v 5 If it's someone between five and twenty, then¦60545 it's twenty silver coins for a male and ten for a female¦60560.
\v 6 Between one month¦60567 old and five years¦60572, it's five silver coins for a male and three¦60581 for a female¦60579.
\v 7 For sixty¦60588 years old and older, it's fifteen silver coins for a male and ten for a female¦60599.
\p
\v 8 If \add @the maker of the vow\add* can't afford the valuation¦60607, then \add @that person\add* must¦60608 stand in front¦60609 of the priest \add and give an account\add*, and then the priest \add ≈can set a value that they can afford\add*.
\p
\v 9 If¦60637 it's an animal that they're \add ≈promising\add* as a gift for Yahweh¦60632, then \add ?≈that animal becomes sacred¦60640\add*—
\v 10 it can't¦60644 be \add ≈exchanged for a different one (either better or worse)\add*, \add ≈but¦60644\add* if it does get substituted, then \add ≈both animals will become sacred¦60666\add*.
\v 11 Any ‘unclean¦60672’ animal cannot be presented to Yahweh¦60679, \add so if that's what was promised\add*, \add @the person\add* must¦60676 take the animal to the priest¦60685,
\v 12 and¦60692 a priest must¦60687 \add ≈give a fair valuation¦60694 according¦60694 to the quality of the animal\add*—the priest's \add ≈decision¦60687 will be final\add*.
\v 13 \add ≈However,\add* if it's later bought back, then¦60699 an extra twenty¦60704 percent¦60703 must¦60702 be added to that valuation¦60707.
\p
\v 14 If someone¦60709 dedicates their house¦60715 as sacred¦60712 to Yahweh¦60717, a priest must¦60712 \add ≈value it according to its quality\add*—the priest's \add ≈decision¦60718 will be final\add*.
\v 15 \add ≈However,\add* if \add ≈that person\add* \add decides to\add* buy back their house¦60737, then an extra twenty¦60739 percent¦60738 must¦60734 be added to the valuation¦60742 and¦60731 then it \add ≈can be theirs again\add*.
\p
\v 16 If someone¦60752 dedicates part of their \add ≈farmland\add* as sacred¦60751 to Yahweh¦60753, then¦60747 \add ≈it will be valued according to how much seed\add* \add would be sown in it\add*—fifty¦60761 silver¦60763 coins for each 130kg of barley¦60760 \add seed required\add*.
\v 17 ⇔That would be its value if it¦60772 was dedicated during the \add ≈restoration celebration\add* year¦60767,
\v 18 \add ≈but¦60774 in the years following,\add* the priest¦60783 must¦60778 calculate¦60780 the field's¦60779 value \add ≈depending on\add* how many years remain¦60791 before the next \add ≈rest\add* year.
\v 19 \add ≈However,\add* if \add @that person\add* \add decides to\add* buy back their land, then an extra twenty¦60808 percent¦60807 must¦60801 be added to the valuation¦60811 and¦60798 then it \add ≈can be theirs again\add*.
\v 20 If \add @the person\add* doesn't buy back the field \add ≈but¦60816\add* sells it to someone else, then¦60816 it can't¦60818 be bought¦60832 back again¦60833.
\v 21 Then¦60835 when the field is released at the next \add ≈rest year\add*, it will be sacred¦60839 to Yahweh¦60840 and¦60835 the \add #priests\add* \add ≈will take ownership\add*.
\p
\v 22 If someone dedicates to Yahweh¦60857 some land that¦60852 they've bought (i.e., it's not part of their clan inheritance),
\v 23 then¦60859 a priest¦60862 must calculate¦60859 the valuation until¦60866 the \add next\add* \add ≈restoration celebration year\add*, and¦60859 it must be paid that same day¦60873 —becoming sacred¦60875 to Yahweh¦60876.
\v 24 In \add ≈that rest\add* year¦60878, the land will return¦60880 to the original owner who \add ≈has it as part of their clan inheritance\add*.
\p
\v 25 All valuations¦60893 will \add ≈be calculated\add* using the standard weights from the sanctuary—the \add ≈silver coin must¦60894 weigh twelve grams\add*.
\p
\v 26 Every¦60922 firstborn¦60905 \add ≈domestic animal\add* (including cows and sheep¦60921) \add automatically\add* belongs¦60908 to Yahweh¦60909, and no person can \add claim to\add* ‘dedicate’ it.
\v 27 \add ≈However,\add* if it's an ‘unclean¦60927’ animal then it must be bought back by paying its valuation plus¦60928 an additional twenty¦60931 percent¦60930, \add ≈but¦60925\add* if it's not bought back, then it must be sold at its valuation \add price\add*.
\p
\v 28 If someone¦60947 dedicates something to Yahweh that they own¦60957 (e.g., a man or an animal, or a field¦60956), they can't¦60958 then sell¦60959 it or buy it \add ?straight\add* back—everything that's dedicated \add like that\add* becomes sacred¦60965 to Yahweh.\x + \xo 27:28: \xt Num 18:14.\x*
\p
\v 29 Any person¦60973 who's dedicated for destruction¦60975 cannot be bought¦60980 back—they must¦60975 be executed.
\p
\v 30 A tenth of all the \add ≈harvests¦60990 from the crops\add* and¦60984 fruit¦60990 from the trees, belongs to Yahweh. It's sacred¦60994 to Yahweh.\x + \xo 27:30-33: \xt Num 18:21; Deu 14:22-29.\x*
\v 31 If someone¦61001 \add really\add* wanted to buy back their tenth \add of their produce\add*, \add an additional\add* twenty¦61003 percent¦61004 must¦61000 be added \add to the valuation\add*.
\v 32 Every tenth¦61018 animal of the \add ≈mustered domestic\add* cattle and sheep and goats, is sacred¦61021 to Yahweh¦61022.
\v 33 \add @The herder\add* mustn't pick out good¦61028 or bad ones, or make substitutions. (If a substitution was made, both animals then become sacred and must¦61025 not be bought back.)
\p
\v 34 \add @The above\add* are the \add ≈instructions¦61049 and rules\add* that¦61048 Yahweh¦61050 \add ≈gave\add* Mosheh¦61053 at Mt¦61058. Sinai¦61059 for the \add ≈Israelis¦61056\add*.
